[[PlayStation 2]])\n*''[[Monsters, Inc. Scream Arena]]'' ([[GameCube]])\n*''[[Monsters, Inc. (video game)|Monsters, Inc.]]'' ([[Game Boy Color]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[PlayStation 2]])\n*''Monsters, Inc. Run'' ([[iPhone]], [[iPod Touch]], [[iPad]])\n*''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]'' ([[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Wii]], [[Wii U]], [[Nintendo 3DS]])\n*''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]'' ([[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]])\n\n==Theme park attractions==\n\n*''[[Monsters, Inc. Ride & Go Seek]]'' at [[Tokyo DisneySea]] at [[Tokyo Disney Resort]].\n===Monsters, Inc. Laugh Floor===\n[[file:MonstersIncLaughFloorSign.jpg|250px|right]]\n'''Monsters, Inc. Laugh Floor''' is an [[comedy club]] attraction in [[Magic Kingdom#Tomorrowland|Tomorrowland]] at [[Magic Kingdom]] at the [[Walt Disney World Resort]].<ref name=\"os\">{{cite news |last1=Boyd |first1=Christopher |last2=Powers |first2=Scott |title=Monsters, Inc. comedy act gives material a test |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-2006-11-20-tourism20-story.html |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=November 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIt  opened on April 2, 2007, replacing the [[Circle-Vision]] attaction [[The Timekeeper]]. The characters from the 2001 and 2013 [[Disney]]/[[Pixar]] animated films ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'' and ''[[Monsters University]]'' that appear in the attraction are [[Mike Wazowski]] ([[Billy Crystal]]) and [[List of Monsters, Inc. characters#Roz|Roz]] ([[Bob Peterson (filmmaker)|Bob Peterson]]). By November 2006, the attraction as Monsters, Inc. Laugh Floor Comedy Club was going through a testing phase with expect regular operation in January 2007.<ref name=\"os\"/>\n\nThe attraction was nominated for the 6th Annual VES Awards - Outstanding Visual Effects in a Special Venue Project in 2008, but lost to Dinosaurs - Giants of Patagonia.<ref>{{cite news |title=6th Annual VES Awards |url=https://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ayear/6th-annual-ves-awards |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=www.visualeffectssociety.com |date=March 24, 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n===Monsters Inc. Mike & Sulley to the Rescue!===\n[[file:Mike_and_Sulley_to_the_Rescue.JPG|250px|left]]\n'''Monsters, Inc. Mike & Sulley to the Rescue!'''  is a [[dark ride]] attraction in Hollywood Land at [[Disney California Adventure]] at the [[Disneyland Resort]] in [[Anaheim, California]]. It is based on the 2001 [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]\u00b7[[Pixar]] film ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'' It opened on January 22, 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Krosnick |first1=Brian |title=Monsters, Inc. Mike and Sulley to the Rescue |url=https://www.themeparktourist.com/guides/disney-california-adventure/monsters-inc-mike-and-sulley-rescue |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=Theme Park Tourist |date=June 9, 2012 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe attraction replaced the short-lived [[Superstar Limo]] dark ride.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eades |first1=Mark |title=Monsters, Inc. Mike & Sulley to the Rescue! |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2015/12/14/monsters-inc-mike-sulley-to-the-rescue/ |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=Orange County Register |date=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons cat|Monsters, Inc.}}\n{{Monsters, Inc.}}\n{{Pixar Animation Studios}}\n{{DisneyConsumer}}\n{{Disney franchises}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Cartoon|Animation}}\n\n[[Category:Monsters, Inc.| ]]\n[[Category:Pixar franchises]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Film series disestablished in 2013]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Animated film series]]\n[[Category:Computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:Film franchises]]\n[[Category:Children's film series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox media franchise\n| title       = ''Monsters, Inc.''\n| image       = Monsters, Inc. logo.svg\n| creator     = [[Pixar Animation Studios]]\n| owner       = [[Disney Enterprises, Inc.]]\n| films       = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Monsters University]]'' (2013)\n}}\n| shorts      = {{Plainlist|\n* ''Charades'' (2001)\n* ''[[Mike's New Car]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Party Central]]'' (2013)\n}}\n| atv         = ''[[Monsters at Work]]'' (2021)\n| vgs         = {{Plainlist|\n* ''[[Monsters, Inc. (video game)|Monsters, Inc.]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Monsters, Inc. Scream Team]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Monsters, Inc. Scream Arena]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]'' (2013)\n* ''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]'' (2019)\n}}\n| soundtracks =\n| music       = ''[[Monsters, Inc. Scream Factory Favorites]]'' (2002)\n| attractions = {{Plainlist|\n* ''Monsters, Inc. Mike & Sulley to the Rescue!'' (2006\u2013present)\n* ''Monsters, Inc. Laugh Floor'' (2007\u2013present)\n* ''[[Monsters, Inc. Ride & Go Seek]]'' (2009\u2013present)\n}}\n}}\n'''''Monsters, Inc.''''' is a [[CGI animated]] [[film series]] and [[Disney]] [[media franchise]] that began with the 2001 film, [[Monsters, Inc.|of the same name]], produced by [[Pixar]] and distributed by [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. The original film was followed by a [[prequel]] film, ''[[Monsters University]]'', released in 2013.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graser|first=Marc|title=Disney drawing 'Monsters Inc.' sequel|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1118018177|accessdate=March 6, 2012|newspaper=Variety|date=April 22, 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe franchise takes place in a fictional universe where Monsters are the primary citizens of society and harness the energy of Humans to power their cities. The company known as ''Monsters, Inc.'' accomplishes this by patenting doors which lead to the Human world.\n\n==Feature films==\n===''Monsters, Inc.'' (2001)===\n{{Main|Monsters, Inc.}}\nThe first film introduces the monster world, where Monstropolis is powered by the screams of human children as monsters enter the human world at night. When a little girl accidentally enters the monster world, friends Mike and Sulley must find a way to hide her from the authorities and return her to her own world, and in the process learn that not everything they have been led to believe about humans is true. The film surpassed ''[[Toy Story 2]]'' and peaked as the second [[highest-grossing animated films|highest-grossing animated film]] of all time, behind only 1994's ''The Lion King'' at the time.<ref name=\"PixarTouch201\">Price, p. 201</ref> It was one of the first animated films to be nominated for the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature]] but lost to ''[[Shrek]]''.\n\n===''Monsters University'' (2013)===\n{{Main|Monsters University}}\nA prequel to the first film, ''Monsters University'' tells Mike and Sulley's backstory. The future friends meet at college and initially start off as enemies, but end up on the same team in the university's \"Scare Games\", where they and their team of misfits must beat the odds and win the competition, or be expelled from school. As the team struggles, the two learn to work together, and slowly become best friends.\n\n==Television series==\n{{Main|Monsters at Work}}\n''Monsters at Work'' is upcoming television series spin-off of ''Monsters, Inc.'' produced by [[Disney Television Animation]] for [[Disney+]]. The spin-off of ''Monsters, Inc.'' was confirmed in a Disney press release on November 9, 2017 as part oflist of in development series for [[The Walt Disney Company]]'s upcoming streaming service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/biz/news/star-wars-tv-series-disney-streaming-service-1202611408/|title=New \u2018Star Wars\u2019 Trilogy in Works With Rian Johnson, TV Series Also Coming to Disney Streaming Service|first=Cynthia|last=Littleton|date=9 November 2017|publisher=Variety}}</ref> On April 9, 2019, it was revealed that the show would be titled ''Monsters at Work'' and premiere in Spring 2021.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1232747074829082624|user=tranloan|date=February 26, 2020|title=Stephen Anderson confirms that a 10 episode season of Monsters At Work will tentatively premiere on Disney+ in Spring 2021. Kelly Marie Tran will loan her voice to the show as Val Little. (Source: @podWAM)}}</ref> Five of the original cast would return including [[John Goodman]] and [[Billy Crystal]] reprising their roles as Sulley and Mike, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/04/monsters-at-work-billy-crystal-john-goodman-reprise-monsters-inc-voice-roles-disney-plus-animated-series-1202591950/|title=\u2018Monsters At Work\u2019: Billy Crystal & John Goodman To Reprise \u2018Monsters, Inc.\u2019 Voice Roles On Disney+ Animated Series|website=Deadline|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=April 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIts premise is following a young eager mechanic, Tylor Tuskmon ([[Ben Feldman]]), six months after the original movie. Tuskmon hopes to be promoted to the Laugh Floor alongside Mike and Sulley.<ref name=thr>{{cite news |last1=Goldberg |first1=Lesley |title='Monsters, Inc.' Voice Cast to Return for Disney+ Series (Exclusive) |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/monsters-voice-cast-return-disney-series-1200367 |accessdate=April 9, 2019 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=April 9, 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Short films==\n===''Charades'' (2001)===\n''Charades''<ref name=TheFilmsOfPixar/> is a two-minute<ref name=HarryPotter/> promotional short animated film, featuring characters from ''Monsters, Inc.''. The short was theatrically released on November 16, 2001 with [[Warner Bros.|Warner Bros. Pictures]]' ''[[Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone]]''. The cast consists of John Goodman and Billy Crystal.<ref name=TheFilmsOfPixar>''Total Film'' June 2018 - \u2018<i>The Films of Pixar</i>\u2019 Magazine</ref>\n\nIn the short, Sulley is shown playing a game of charades with Mike, but Mike is unable to guess the phrase \"[[Harry Potter (film series)|''Harry Potter'']]\". Afterwards, Mike attempts to charade, but a bored Sulley quickly and correctly guesses ''[[Star Wars]]''. A bewildered Mike asks how he does it.<ref name=HarryPotter>{{cite news|last=Trail|first=Mand|title=\u2018Monsters Inc.\u2019 Short Film \u2018Charades'|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vZIY2-kH-wE|accessdate=December 27, 2009|newspaper=Monsters and Critics|date=August 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===''Mike's New Car'' (2002)===\n{{Main|Mike's New Car}}\n\n===''Party Central'' (2013)===\n{{Main|Party Central}}\n''Party Central'' is a six-minute<ref name=EWPartyMuppets /> short animated film, featuring characters from ''Monsters University''. It premiered on August 9, 2013, at the [[Disney D23#D23 Expo|D23 Expo]]. The short was set to be released theatrically with ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]'' in 2014,<ref name=SlashParty /> before the film was pushed back to 2015. Instead, it was theatrically released on March 21, 2014, with ''[[Muppets Most Wanted]]''.<ref name=EWPartyMuppets>{{cite news|last=Rottenberg|first=Josh|title=Disney to showcase new Pixar short 'Party Central' in front of 'Muppets Most Wanted' - EXCLUSIVE|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2014/01/07/disney-pixar-short-party-central-muppets-most-wanted/|accessdate=January 7, 2014|newspaper=Entertainment Weekly|date=January 7, 2014}}</ref> The short was written and directed by Kelsey Mann, story supervisor on ''Monsters University''.<ref name=EWPartyMuppets /> The cast consists of Billy Crystal, John Goodman, Peter Sohn, Julia Sweeney, Charlie Day, Nathan Fillion, Dave Foley, Sean Hayes, Bobby Moynihan, and Joel Murray.<ref name=DILookParty>{{cite news|title=Just Released: First Look at Party Central Short|url=http://blogs.disney.com/insider/2014/01/07/just-released-first-look-at-party-central-short/|accessdate=January 7, 2014|newspaper=Disney Insider|date=January 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the short, the Oozma Kappa fraternity organizes a party, but no one shows up. To solve the problem, they use door stations to steal visitors from the biggest party going on at another fraternity.<ref name=SlashParty>{{cite news|last=Fischer|first=Russ|title=\u2018Monsters University\u2019 Short Film \u2018Party Central\u2019 Revealed|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/disney-debuts-monsters-u-short-party-central-at-d23/|accessdate=August 9, 2013|newspaper=/Film|date=August 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n{{details|Monsters, Inc.#Reception|Monsters University#Reception|topic=the reception of each film}}\n\n===Box office performance===\nThe film series has grossed a total of $1,306,110,769, making the ''Monsters, Inc.'' franchise the [[List of highest-grossing animated films#Highest-grossing animated franchises and film series|Ninth highest-grossing animated film franchise]].\n\n''Monsters, Inc.'' ranked {{Abbr|No.|Number}} 1 at the box office its opening weekend, grossing $62,577,067 in North America alone. The film had a small drop-off of 27.2% over its second weekend, earning another $45,551,028. In its third weekend, the film experienced a larger decline of 50.1%, placing itself in the second position just after ''[[Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (film)|Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone]]''. In its fourth weekend, however, there was an increase of 5.9%. Making $24,055,001 that weekend for a combined total of over $562 million. It is the seventh biggest (in US$) fourth weekend ever for a film.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekend&id=monstersinc.htm|title=Monsters, Inc. \u2013 Weekend Grosses|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/alltime/weekends/moreweekends.htm?page=4&p=.htm|title=Top Weekends: 2nd&nbsp;\u2013 12th&nbsp;\u2014 Weekend Grosses|publisher=Box Office Mojo|accessdate=September 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n''Monsters University'' has earned $268,227,670 in North America, and $475,066,843 in other territories, for a worldwide total of $743,294,513.<ref name=BOMMU>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=monstersinc2.htm |title=Monsters University (2013) |publisher=Box Office Mojo |date= |accessdate=June 24, 2013}}</ref> The film earned $136.9 million on its opening weekend worldwide. For unknown reasons, Disney declined to provide a budget for the film, although BoxOffice.com cites a budget of a total of $270 million.<ref name=BoxOffice>{{cite web|title=Monsters University (G)|url=http://www.boxoffice.com/statistics/movies/monsters-inc-2-2012|publisher=Box Office|accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' speculated that it was higher than that of ''[[Brave (2012 film)|Brave]]'' ($185 million), mostly due to high cost of John Goodman and Billy Crystal reprising their roles.<ref name=EW1stWeekend>{{cite web|url=http://insidemovies.ew.com/2013/06/23/box-office-report-monsters-university-world-war-z/ |title=Box Office report: 'Monsters University' scares up $82 million, 'World War Z' shatters expectations |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=June 23, 2013 |accessdate=June 23, 2013}}</ref> Shockya, a subsidiary website of [[CraveOnline]], estimated the budget to be $200 million, on par with ''[[Toy Story 3]]'' and ''[[Cars 2]]''.<ref name=\"Shockya\">{{cite web |last= Belcastro |first= Joe|title= Box Office Report: Monsters University schools The Heat and White House Down |url= http://www.shockya.com/news/2013/06/30/box-office-report-monsters-university-schools-the-heat-and-white-house-down/ |work= Shockya |accessdate= July 8, 2013}}</ref> \n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=99% border=\"1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Film\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Release date\n! colspan=\"3\"| Box office gross\n! colspan=\"2\" text=\"wrap\"| Box office ranking\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Budget\n! rowspan=\"2\"| {{nowrap|{{Abbr|Ref(s)|References}}}}\n|-\n! North America\n! Other territories\n! Worldwide\n! All time<br>North America\n! All time<br>worldwide\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: left;\"| '''''Monsters, Inc.'''''\n| '''{{dts|2001|11|2}}'''\n| '''$289,916,256'''\n| '''$272,900,000'''\n| '''$562,816,256'''\n| '''#74'''\n| '''#126'''\n| '''$115,000,000'''\n| <ref name=BOMMI>{{cite web|title=Monsters, Inc|url=http://boxofficemojo.com/mov