t]]\n| {{N/A|''Photograph''}}\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Thaddeus \"Phlegm\" Bile\n| [[Jeff Pidgeon]]\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! George Sanderson\n| Samuel Lord Black\n| {{N/A|''Silent role''}}\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| {{N/A|''Silent cameo''}}\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Charlie\n| [[Philip Proctor]]\n| {{N/A|''Silent cameo''}}\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Peter \"Claws\" Ward\n| [[Joe Ranft]]\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Dean Abigail Hardscrabble\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Helen Mirren]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Scott \"Squishy\" Squibbles\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Peter Sohn]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Peter Sohn\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Don Carlton\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Joel Murray]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Joel Murray\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Terry Perry\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Dave Foley]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Dave Foley\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Terri Perry\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Sean Hayes]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Sean Hayes\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Art\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Charlie Day]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Charlie Day\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Sherri Squibbles\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Julia Sweeney]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Julia Sweeney\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Johnny J. Worthington lll\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Nathan Fillion]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Nathan Fillion\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Chet Alexander\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Bobby Moynihan]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Bobby Moynihan\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Professor Derek Knight\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Alfred Molina]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Brock Pearson\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Tyler Labine]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Claire Wheeler\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Aubrey Plaza]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Carrie Williams\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Beth Behrs]]\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Beth Behrs\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Mrs. Karen Graves\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Bonnie Hunt\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! \"Frightening\" Frank McCay\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[John Krasinski]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Referee\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| rowspan=\"2\" | [[Bill Hader]]\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Slug\n| style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n|-\n! Tylor Tuskmon\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Ben Feldman]]\n|-\n! Val Little\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Kelly Marie Tran]]\n|-\n! Fritz\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Henry Winkler]]\n|-\n! Bernard\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| John Ratzenberger\n|-\n! Roze\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| Bob Peterson\n|-\n! Duncan\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Lucas Neff]]\n|-\n! Cutter\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Alanna Ubach]]\n|-\n! Millie Tuskmon\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"background-color:lightgrey;\" |\n| [[Aisha Tyler]]\n|}\n* '''Note''': A grey cell indicates the character was not in the film.\n\n== Crew ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Film\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Director(s)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Producer(s)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Executive Producer(s)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Writer(s)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Composer\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"| Editor(s)\n|-\n| ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Pete Docter]]<br />''{{small|Co-directed by:}}'' [[Lee Unkrich]] & [[David Silverman (animator)|David Silverman]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Darla K. Anderson]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[John Lasseter]] & [[Andrew Stanton]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''{{small|Screenplay by:}}'' Andrew Stanton & [[Daniel Gerson]] <br>''{{small|Original Story by:}}'' Pete Docter, [[Jill Culton]], [[Jeff Pidgeon]] & [[Ralph Eggleston]]\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Randy Newman]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Robert Grahamjones & Jim Stewart\n|-\n| ''[[Monsters University]]''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Dan Scanlon]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Kori Rae\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[John Lasseter]], [[Pete Docter]], [[Andrew Stanton]] & [[Lee Unkrich]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| ''{{small|Screenplay by:}}'' Daniel Gerson, Robert L. Baird & Dan Scanlon<br>''{{small|Story by:}}'' Dan Scanlon, Daniel Gerson & Robert L. Baird\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| Greg Snyder\n|}\n\n==Video games==\n*''[[Monsters, Inc. Scream Team]]'' ([[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 2]])\n*''[[Monsters, Inc. Scream Arena]]'' ([[GameCube]])\n*''[[Monsters, Inc. (video game)|Monsters, Inc.]]'' ([[Game Boy Color]], [[Game Boy Advance]], [[PlayStation 2]])\n*''Monsters, Inc. Run'' ([[iPhone]], [[iPod Touch]], [[iPad]])\n*''[[Disney Infinity (video game)|Disney Infinity]]'' ([[PlayStation 3]], [[Xbox 360]], [[Wii]], [[Wii U]], [[Nintendo 3DS]])\n*''[[Kingdom Hearts III]]'' ([[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox One]])\n\n==Theme park attractions==\n\n*''[[Monsters, Inc. Ride & Go Seek]]'' at [[Tokyo DisneySea]] at [[Tokyo Disney Resort]].\n===Monsters, Inc. Laugh Floor===\n[[file:MonstersIncLaughFloorSign.jpg|250px|right]]\n'''Monsters, Inc. Laugh Floor''' is an [[comedy club]] attraction in [[Magic Kingdom#Tomorrowland|Tomorrowland]] at [[Magic Kingdom]] at the [[Walt Disney World Resort]].<ref name=\"os\">{{cite news |last1=Boyd |first1=Christopher |last2=Powers |first2=Scott |title=Monsters, Inc. comedy act gives material a test |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-2006-11-20-tourism20-story.html |accessdate=August 1, 2019 |work=Orlando Sentinel |date=November 20, 2006}}</ref>\n\nIt  opened on April 2, 2007, replacing the [[Circle-Vision]] attaction [[The Timekeeper]]. The characters from the 2001 and 2013 [[Disney]]/[[Pixar]] animated films ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'' and ''[[Monsters University]]'' that appear in the attraction are [[Mike Wazowski]] ([[Billy Crystal]]) and [[List of Monsters, Inc. characters#Roz|Roz]] ([[Bob Peterson (filmmaker)|Bob Peterson]]). By November 2006, the attraction as Monsters, Inc. Laugh Floor Comedy Club was going through a testing phase with expect regular operation in January 2007.<ref name=\"os\"/>\n\nThe attraction was nominated for the 6th Annual VES Awards - Outstanding Visual Effects in a Special Venue Project in 2008, but lost to Dinosaurs - Giants of Patagonia.<ref>{{cite news |title=6th Annual VES Awards |url=https://www.visualeffectssociety.com/ayear/6th-annual-ves-awards |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=www.visualeffectssociety.com |date=March 24, 2015 |language=en}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n===Monsters Inc. Mike & Sulley to the Rescue!===\n[[file:Mike_and_Sulley_to_the_Rescue.JPG|250px|left]]\n'''Monsters, Inc. Mike & Sulley to the Rescue!'''  is a [[dark ride]] attraction in Hollywood Land at [[Disney California Adventure]] at the [[Disneyland Resort]] in [[Anaheim, California]]. It is based on the 2001 [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]]\u00b7[[Pixar]] film ''[[Monsters, Inc.]]'' It opened on January 22, 2006.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Krosnick |first1=Brian |title=Monsters, Inc. Mike and Sulley to the Rescue |url=https://www.themeparktourist.com/guides/disney-california-adventure/monsters-inc-mike-and-sulley-rescue |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=Theme Park Tourist |date=June 9, 2012 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nThe attraction replaced the short-lived [[Superstar Limo]] dark ride.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Eades |first1=Mark |title=Monsters, Inc. Mike & Sulley to the Rescue! |url=https://www.ocregister.com/2015/12/14/monsters-inc-mike-sulley-to-the-rescue/ |accessdate=July 31, 2019 |work=Orange County Register |date=December 14, 2015}}</ref>\n{{-}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Commons cat|Monsters, Inc.}}\n{{Monsters, Inc.}}\n{{Pixar Animation Studios}}\n{{DisneyConsumer}}\n{{Disney franchises}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Cartoon|Animation}}\n\n[[Category:Monsters, Inc.| ]]\n[[Category:Pixar franchises]]\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 2001]]\n[[Category:Film series disestablished in 2013]]\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Animated film series]]\n[[Category:Computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:Film franchises]]\n[[Category:Children's film series]]\n", "name_user": "2601:cb:8200:7220:64d9:2601:388d:416", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monsters,_Inc._(franchise)"}
{"title_page": "Samanid Empire", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian empire ruled by the Samanids}}\n{{Infobox country\n|native_name            = \u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646\n|conventional_long_name = Samanid Empire\n|common_name            = Samanid Empire\n|era                    = [[Middle Ages]]\n|status                 = Empire\n|status_text            =\n|empire                 =\n|government_type        = Emirate\n|year_start             = 819\n|year_end               = 999\n|event_start            =\n|date_start             =\n|event_end              =\n|date_end               =\n|p1                     = Saffarid dynasty\n|flag_p1                = Saffarid dynasty 861-1003.png\n|p2                     = Abbasid Caliphate\n|flag_p2                = Abbasids850.png\n|p3                     = Alid dynasties of northern Iran\n|flag_p3                = Alavids-map.png\n|p4                     = Banijurids\n|flag_p4                =\n|p5                     = Bukhar Khudahs\n|flag_p5                =\n|p6                     = Principality of Ushrusana\n|flag_p6                =\n|p7                     = Principality of Farghana\n|flag_p7                =\n|p8                     = Sogdia\n|image_p8               = [[Image:TarkhunSogdianCoin.jpg|25px]]\n|s1                     = Ghaznavid dynasty\n|flag_s1                = Ghaznavid Empire 975 - 1187 (AD).PNG\n|s2                     = Karakhanids\n|flag_s2                = KaraKhanidAD1000.png\n|s3                     = Banu Ilyas\n|flag_s3                = BanuIlyasMapHistoryofIran.png\n|s4                     = Farighunids\n|flag_s4                =\n|s5                     = Muhtajids\n|flag_s5                =\n|s6                     = Buyid dynasty\n|flag_s6                =\n|image_flag             =\n|flag                   =\n|flag_type              =\n|image_coat             =\n|image_map              = Samanid dynasty (819\u2013999).GIF\n|image_map_caption      = The Samanid Empire at its greatest extent under [[Ismail Samani]]\n|capital                = {{plainlist|\n* [[Samarkand]] {{small|(819\u2013892)}}\n* [[Bukhara]] {{small|(892\u2013999)}}\n}}\n|common_languages       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Persian language|Persian]] ({{small|[[lingua franca]], court, academia}}),<ref>\"Persian Prose Literature.\" World Eras. 2002. HighBeam Research. (September 3, 2012);\"''Princes, although they were often tutored in Arabic and religious subjects, frequently did not feel as comfortable with the Arabic language and preferred literature in Persian, which was either their mother tongue\u2014as in the case of dynasties such as the Saffarids (861\u20131003), Samanids (873\u20131005), and Buyids (945\u20131055)...''\". [https://web.archive.org/web/20130502180821/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3034700041.html]</ref><ref>Elton L. Daniel, ''History of Iran'', (Greenwood Press, 2001), 74.</ref>{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=146}}<ref name=\"Paul Bergne 6\">{{cite book|author=Paul Bergne|title=The Birth of Tajikistan: National Identity and the Origins of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3coojMwTKU8C&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 June 2007|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-283-7|pages=6\u2013}}</ref>\n*[[Arabic]] ({{small|theology}}){{sfn|Frye|1975|p=145}}\n}}\n|religion               = [[Sunni Islam]] ({{small|minority [[Shia Islam]], [[Nestorian Christianity|Nestorianism]], [[Zoroastrianism]]}})\n|currency               =\n|leader1                = [[Ahmad ibn Asad]]\n|leader2                = [[Abd al-Malik II (Samanid emir)|'Abd al-Malik II]]\n|year_leader1           = 819\u2013864/5\n|year_leader2           = 999\n|title_leader           = [[Emir]]\n|stat_year1   = 928 est.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Turchin|first1=Peter|last2=Adams|first2=Jonathan M.|last3=Hall|first3=Thomas D | title = East-West Orientation of Historical Empires | journal = Journal of World-systems Research|date=December 2006 |volume=12|issue=2 |page=222 |url =http://jwsr.pitt.edu/ojs/index.php/jwsr/article/view/369/381|accessdate=12 September 2016 |issn= 1076-156X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taagepera|first=Rein|year=1997|title=Expansion and Contraction Patterns of Large Polities: Context for Russia|journal=International Studies Quarterly|volume=41|issue=3|pages=475\u2013504|doi=10.1111/0020-8833.00053|jstor=2600793|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/3cn68807}}</ref>\n|stat_area1   = 2850000\n}}\n{{History of Iran}}\nThe '''Samanid Empire''' ({{lang-fa|\u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646}}, ''S\u0101m\u0101niy\u0101n'', also known as the '''Samanian Empire''', '''Samanid dynasty''', '''Samanid Emirate''', or simply '''Samanids''') was a [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=151}} [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] empire{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=164}} from 819 to 999. The empire was centered in [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] and [[Transoxiana]] during its existence; at its greatest extent, the empire encompassed all of today's [[Afghanistan]], large parts of [[Iran]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Turkmenistan]], [[Uzbekistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], and parts of [[Kazakhstan]] and [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taagepera|first=Rein|date=1997-01-01|title=Expansion and Contraction Patterns of Large Polities: Context for Russia|jstor=2600793|journal=International Studies Quarterly|volume=41|issue=3|pages=475\u2013504|doi=10.1111/0020-8833.00053|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/3cn68807}}</ref>\n\nThe Samanid state was founded by four brothers; [[Nuh ibn Asad|Nuh]], [[Ahmad ibn Asad|Ahmad]], [[Yahya ibn Asad|Yahya]], and [[Ilyas ibn Asad|Ilyas]]\u2014each of them ruled their own territory under Abbasid suzerainty. In 892, [[Ismail Samani]] (892\u2013907) united the Samanid state under one ruler, thus effectively putting an end to the [[feudal]] system used by the Samanids. It was also under him that the Samanids became independent of Abbasid authority.\n\nThe Samanid Empire is part of the [[Iranian Intermezzo]], which saw the creation of a [[Persianate society|Persianate]] culture and identity that brought Iranian speech and traditions into the fold of the [[Muslim world|Islamic world]]. This would later lead to the formation of the [[Turko-Persian tradition|Turko-Persian]] culture.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Turko-Persia in Historical Perspective|last = Canfield L.|first = Robert|publisher = Cambridge University Press|year = 2002|isbn = 9780521522915|location = |pages = 12 }}</ref>\n\nThe Samanids promoted the arts, giving rise to the advancement of science and literature, and thus attracted scholars such as [[Rudaki]], [[Ferdowsi]], and [[Avicenna]]. While under Samanid control, [[Bukhara]] was a rival to [[Baghdad]] in its glory.<ref name=\"Elton L. Daniel pg. 74\">''The History of Iran'' by Elton L. Daniel, pg. 74</ref> Scholars note that the Samanids revived [[Persian language]] and culture more than the [[Buyids]] and the Saffarids, while continuing to patronize [[Arabic]] for sciences as well as the religious studies. They considered themselves to be descendants of the [[Sasanian Empire]].{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=145-146}}<ref name=\"Elton L. Daniel pg. 74\"/> In a famous edict, Samanid authorities declared that \"here, in this region, the language is [[Persian language|Persian]], and the kings of this realm are Persian kings.\"<ref name=\"Elton L. Daniel pg. 74\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nThe eponymous ancestor of the Samanid dynasty was [[Saman Khuda]], a [[Persian people|Persian]] noble who belonged to a ''[[dehqan]]'' family, which was a class of land-owning magnates. The original home of the Samanids is unclear, for some [[Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] texts claim that the name was derived from a village near [[Samarkand]], while others assert it was a village near [[Balkh]] or [[Termez|Tirmidh]]. The latter is more probable since the earliest appearance of the Samanid family appears to be in [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] rather than [[Transoxiana]].<ref name=\"The Cambridge History of Iran\">{{cite book|last1=Frye|first1=Richard N.|title=The Cambridge History of Iran|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=136}}</ref> In some sources the Samanids claimed to be descended from the noble [[House of Mihran|Mihran family]] of [[Bahram Chobin]], whereas one author claimed that they belonged to the Turkish Oghuz tribe, although this is most unlikely.<ref name=\"The Cambridge History of Iran\"/> Originally a [[Zoroastrian]], Saman Khuda converted to [[Islam]] during the governorship of [[Asad ibn Abdallah al-Qasri]] in [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]],{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=136}} and named his oldest son as [[Asad ibn Saman|Asad]] in the governor's honour.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|p=685}} In 819, the governor of Khorasan, [[Ghassan ibn Abbad]], rewarded the four sons of Asad for their aid against the rebel [[Rafi ibn al-Layth]]; [[Nuh ibn Asad|Nuh]] received [[Samarkand]]; [[Ahmad ibn Asad|Ahmad]] received [[Farghana]]; [[Yahya ibn Asad|Yahya]] received [[Tashkent|Shash]]; and [[Ilyas ibn Asad|Ilyas]] received [[Herat]].{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=136}} This marked the beginning of the Samanid dynasty.\n\n===Rise===\n\n====The Samanid branch in Herat (819\u2013857)====\n\nIlyas died in 856, and was succeeded by his son [[Ibrahim ibn Ilyas]]\u2014the [[Tahirid dynasty|Tahirid]] governor of Khorasan, [[Muhammad ibn Tahir]], thereafter appointed him as the commander of his army, and sent him on an expedition against the [[Saffarid dynasty|Saffarid]] ruler [[Ya'qub ibn al-Layth al-Saffar]] in [[Sistan]]. He was defeated at a battle near [[Pushang]] in 857, and fled to [[Nishapur]], where he was captured by Ya'qub al-Saffar and sent to Sistan as a hostage.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=136}} The Tahirids thereafter assumed direct control over Herat.\n\n====The Samanid branches in Transoxiana (819\u2013892)====\n{{See Also|Samanid Civil War of 888}}\n[[File:Transoxiana 8th century.svg|thumb|right|300px|Map of [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] and [[Transoxiana]].]]\nIn 839/40, Nuh seized [[Isfijab]] from the nomadic [[Paganism|pagan]] [[Oghuz Turks|Turks]] living in the [[steppe]]. He thereafter had a wall constructed around the city to protect it from their attacks. He died in 841/2\u2014his two brothers Yahya and Ahmad were then appointed as the joint rulers of the city by the Tahirid governor of Khorasan.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=136}} After Yahya's death in 855, Ahmad took control over Ch\u00e2ch, thus becoming the ruler of most of [[Transoxiana]]. He died in 864/5; his son [[Nasr I]] received Farghana and Samarkand, while his other son [[Ya'qub ibn Ahmad|Ya'qub]] received Ch\u00e2ch (areas around modern Tashkent/Chachkent).{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=137}} Meanwhile, the Tahirids' authority had significantly weakened after suffering several defeats by the Saffarid ruler Ya'qub al-Saffar, thus losing their grip over the Samanids, who became more or less independent. Nasr I used this opportunity to strengthen his authority by sending his brother [[Ismail Samani|Ismail]] to [[Bukhara]], which was in an unstable condition after suffering from raids by the [[Afrighids|Afrighid dynasty]] of [[Khwarazm]]. When Ismail reached the city, he was warmly received by its inhabitants, who saw him as one who could restore order.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=137}} Regardless, the [[Bukhar Khudahs]] continued to autonomously rule in Bukhara for a few more years.\n\nAfter not so long, disagreement over where tax money should be distributed started a conflict between the brothers. Ismail was eventually victorious in the dynastic struggle, and took control of the Samanid state. However, Nasr had been the one who had been invested with Transoxiana, and the Abbasid [[caliph]]s continued to recognize him as the rightful ruler. Because of this, Ismail continued to recognize his brother as well, but Nasr was completely powerless, a situation that would continue until his death in August 892.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=137}}\n\n===Final unification and height of power (892\u2013907)===\n[[File:13 Buhara Mavzolej Ismaila Samanija (2).JPG|thumb|right|300px|Picture of the [[Samanid Mausoleum]], the burial site of [[Ismail Samani]].]]\nA few months later, Ya'qub al-Saffar also died and was succeeded by his brother [[Amr ibn al-Layth]], who saw himself as the heir of the Tahirids, thus claiming Transoxiana, Khorasan and other parts of Iran for himself. He thereafter forced the Abbasid caliph to recognize him as the ruler of those territories. In the spring of 900, he [[Battle of Balkh|clashed]] with Ismail near [[Balkh]], but was defeated and taken to captivity. Ismail thereafter sent him Baghdad, where he was executed.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=138}} Ismail was thereafter recognized as the ruler of all of Khorasan and Transoxiana by the caliph.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=138}} Furthermore, he also received the investiture over [[Tabaristan]], [[Ray, Iran|Ray]] and [[Isfahan]].{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=138}} It was also during this period that the Afrighid dynasty was forced into submission.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=138}}\n\nBefore his major victory against the Saffarids, he had made various expeditions in Transoxiana; in 892, he put an end to the [[Principality of Ushrusana]] by seizing all of its lands. During the same period, he put an end to the Bukhar Khudas in Bukhara. In 893, he invaded the territories of the [[Karluk Turks]], taking [[Taraz|Talas]] and converting the [[Church of the East|Nestorian church]] there into a [[mosque]].<ref>Renee Grousset, ''The Empire of the Steppes:A History of Central Asia'', Transl. Naomi Walford, (Rutgers University Press, 1991), 142.</ref><ref>\"Samanids\", C. E. Bosworth, ''The Encyclopedia of Islam'', Vol. VIII, Ed. C. E. Bosworth, E. van Donzel, W.P. Heinrichs and G. Lecomte, (E.J. Brill, 1995), 1026.</ref>\n\nIn 900, Ismail sent an army under [[Muhammad ibn Harun al-Sarakhsi]] against [[Muhammad ibn Zayd]], the [[Alid dynasties of northern Iran|Zaydi]] ruler of Tabaristan and [[Gorgan]]. The invasion was successful; Muhammad ibn Zayd was killed and Tabaristan was conquered by the Samanids. However, Muhammad ibn Harun shortly revolted, forcing Ismail himself to invade the region the following year. Muhammad ibn Harun thereafter fled to [[Daylam]], while Ismail reconquered Tabaristan and Gorgan.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=140}} In 901, [[Amr ibn al-Layth|Amr Saffari]] was defeated at the battle of Balkh by the Samanids, which reduced the Saffarid dynasty to a minor tributary in Sistan.{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=35}} It was during this period that the Samanids were at their height of power, ruling as far as [[Qazvin]] in the west<ref name=\"iranicaonline.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/esmail-b-ahmad-b-asad-samani |title=ESM\u0100\u02bf\u012aL, b. A\u1e25mad b. Asad S\u0100M\u0100N\u012a, AB\u016a EBR\u0100H\u012aM |last1=Bosworth |first1=C. Edmund |authorlink1=Clifford Edmund Bosworth |date=15 December 1998 |website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica |accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref> and [[Peshawar]] in the east.\n\nIsmail is known in history as a competent general and a strong ruler; many stories about him are written in Arabic and Persian sources. Furthermore, because of his campaigns in the north, his empire was so safe from enemy incursions that the defences of Bukhara and Samarkand went unused. However, this later had consequences; at the end of the dynasty, the walls--earlier strong, but now falling apart--were greatly missed by the Samanids, who were constantly under attack by the [[Karakhanids]] and other enemies.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=140}}\n\nIsmail died in November 907, and was succeeded by his son [[Ahmad Samani]] (r. 907\u2013914).\n\n===Intermediate period (907\u2013961)===\nNot long after his accession, Ahmad invaded Sistan; by 911, Sistan was under complete Samanid control, and Ahmad's cousin [[Abu Salih Mansur]] was appointed as its governor. Meanwhile, an [[Alids|Alid]] named [[Hasan al-Utrush]] was slowly re-establishing Zaydi over Tabaristan. In 913, Ahmad sent an army under [[Muhammad ibn Sa'luk]] to deal with him. Although the Samanid army was much larger, Hasan managed to emerge victorious. Ahmad, before he could plan another expedition to Tabaristan, was the following year murdered by some of his slaves in a tent near Bukhara.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=141}} During his reign, Ahmad is also said to have replaced the language of the court from Persian to [[Arabic]], which made him unpopular among his subjects, and forced him to change it back to Persian. After Ahmad's death, his eight-year-old son [[Nasr II]] (r. 914\u2013943) succeeded him.\n[[File:NasrIISamanidCoinHistoryofIran.jpg|thumb|right|Coin of [[Nasr II]], minted in [[Nishapur]] (933/4).]]\nDue to Nasr's youth, his prime minister [[Abu 'Abd-Allah al-Jaihani]] took care over most of the state affairs. Jaihani was not only an experienced administrator, but also a prominent geographer and greatly educated man. Almost right after Nasr II had ascended the throne, several revolts erupted, the most dangerous one being under his paternal grand-uncle, [[Ishaq ibn Ahmad]], who seized Samarkand and began minting coins there, while his son Abu Salih Mansur seized [[Nishapur]] and several cities in Khorasan. Ishaq was eventually defeated and captured, while Abu Salih Mansur died of natural causes in 915.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=141}} Some time later Nasr II once again had to deal with rebels; in 919, the governor of Khorasan, [[Husayn ibn Ali Marvarrudhi]], rebelled against Samanid authority. Nasr responded by sending an army under [[Ahmad ibn Sahl]] to suppress the rebellion, which the latter managed to accomplish. After a few weeks, however, Ahmad shortly rebelled himself at Nishapur, made incursions into Gorgan, and then fortified himself in [[Merv]] to avoid a Samanid counter-attack. Nevertheless, the Samanid general [[Hamuya ibn Ali]] managed to lure Ahmad out of Merv, and defeated him in a battle at [[Marw al-Rudh]]; he was captured and imprisoned in Bukhara, where he remained until his death in 920.\n\nIn the west, Nasr II clashed several times with [[Daylamite]] and [[Gilaki people|Gilite]] rulers; In 921, the Zaydids under the Gilite ruler [[Lili ibn al-Nu'man]] invaded Khorasan, but were defeated by the [[Simjurids|Simjurid]] general [[Simjur al-Dawati]]. Later in 930, a Dailamite military leader, [[Makan ibn Kaki]], seized Tabaristan and Gurgan, and even took possession of Nishapur in western Khorasan. He was, however, forced to withdraw back to Tabaristan one year later, due to the threat that Samanids posed.<ref name=\"EI2-164\">Nazim (1987), p. 164</ref><ref>Madelung (1975), pp. 211\u2013212</ref> Makan then returned to Tabaristan, where he was defeated by the [[Ziyarid]] ruler [[Mardavij]], who managed to conquer the region.<ref name=\"EI2-164\">Nazim (1987), p. 164</ref><ref name=\"Iran212\">Madelung (1975), p. 212</ref> In 935, Nasr II re-established Samanid control in Gurgan and made Mardavij's successor [[Vushmgir]] his vassal. However, in 939 he declared independence, but was defeated the following year at [[Battle of Iskhabad|Iskhabad]].\n\nIn 943 several Samanid army officers, angry at Nasr's support of [[Isma'ili]] missionaries, formed a conspiracy to murder him. Nasr's son [[Nuh I]], however, learned of the conspiracy. He went to a banquet designed to organize the plot and had the head of their leader cut off. To appease the other officers, he promised to stop the Isma'ili missionaries from continuing their activities. He then convinced his father to abdicate, who died of [[tuberculosis]] after a few months.<ref>''A new text on Ismailism at the Samanid court'', Patricia Crone and Luke Treadwell, '''Texts, documents, and artefacts:Islamic Studies in Honour of D.S. Richards''', ed. Chase F. Robinson, (Brill, 2003), 46.</ref>\n\nRight when Nuh I ascended the throne, a revolt erupted in Khwarazm, which he managed to suppress. Later in 945, he had to deal with the [[Muhtajids|Muhtajid]] ruler [[Abu 'Ali Chaghani]], who refused to relinquish his post as governor of Khorasan to [[Ibrahim ibn Simjur]]. Abu 'Ali Chaghani then rebelled, and was joined by several prominent figures such as [[Abu Mansur Muhammad]], whom he appointed as his commander-in-chief. In 947, he installed Nuh's uncle [[Ibrahim ibn Ahmad]] as ''amir'' in Bukhara. Abu 'Ali Chaghani then returned to his domains in [[Chaghaniyan]]. Ibrahim, however, was unpopular with the people of Bukhara, and Nuh soon retaliated by retaking the city and blinding Ibrahim and two brothers.\n\nWhen Abu Ali Chaghani received the news of the re-capture of Bukhara, he once again marched towards it, but was defeated by an army sent by Nuh and withdrew back to Chaghaniyan. After some time, he left the region and tried to obtain support from other Samanid vassals. Meanwhile, Nuh had Chaghaniyan ravaged{{sfn|Bosworth|2011|p=63}} and its capital sacked.{{sfn|Frye|1975|pp=149\u2013151}} Another battle shortly ensued between Abu 'Ali Chaghani and a Samanid army in [[Tukharistan]], which resulted in a Samanid victory. Fortunately for Abu Ali Chaghani, he managed to secure the support of other Samanid vassals, such as the rulers of [[Khuttal]], and the Kumiji [[mountain people]], but in the end made peace with Nuh, who allowed him to keep Chaghaniyan in return for sending his son [[Abu'l Muzaffar Abdallah]] as hostage to Bukhara.{{sfn|Bosworth|2011|p=63}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1984|pp=764\u2013766}}\n[[File:Iran circa 1000AD.png|thumb|right|250px|[[Iran]] in the mid-10th century.]]\n[[Alp Tigin]], nominal vassal of the Samanids, conquered Ghazna in 962 from the Lawik dynasty.<ref>He dispossessed an indigenous family who had ruled in [[Ghazni]], the Lawiks (?), and following him a series of slave commanders, ruled there as nominal vassals of the Samanids; they struck coins but placed the names of the Samanids on them</ref><ref>Gard\u012bz\u012b, ed. \u1e24ab\u012bb\u012b, pp. 161\u201362; J\u016bzj\u0101n\u012b, \u1e6cabaq\u0101t, I, pp. 226\u201327; Ne\u1e93\u0101m-al-Molk, pp. 142\u201358; \u0160ab\u0101nk\u0101ra\u02be\u012b, pp. 29\u201334; Bosworth, 1965, pp. 16\u201321</ref> The fifth of these commanders was Seb\u00fcktigin, who governed \u1e20azna for twenty years till 387 AH/997 CE with the title (as it appears from his tomb inscription<ref>Flury, pp. 62\u201363</ref>) of al-\u1e25\u0101jeb al-ajall (most noble commander). He would later be the founder of an independent dynasty based in Ghazna, following the decline of the Samanid Empire in the 990s.<ref>[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ghaznavids \"GHAZNAVIDS\"] ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]]''. Retrieved 17 August 2014</ref>\n\n===Decline and fall (961\u2013999)===\nThe power of the Samanids began to crumble in the latter half of the 10th century. In 962, one the [[Ghilman|ghulams]], [[Alp Tigin]], commander of the army in Khorasan, seized [[Ghazna]] and established himself there.<ref name=\"sinor\">{{citation |year=1990|title=The Cambridge History of Early Inner Asia|editor-last=Sinor|editor-first=Denis|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521243049}}</ref> His successors, however, including [[Seb\u00fck Tigin]], continued to rule as Samanid \"governors\". With the weakened Samanids facing rising challenges from the [[Karakhanid]]s for control of [[Transoxiana]], Seb\u00fck later took control of all the provinces south of the Oxus and established the [[Ghaznavids|Ghaznavid Empire]].\n\nIn 992, a [[Kara-Khanid dynasty|Karakhanid]], Harun Bughra Khan, grandson of the paramount tribal chief of the [[Karluks|Karluk]] confederation [[Sultan Satuq Bughra Khan]], captured [[Bukhara]], the Samanid capital.<ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{citation|last=Davidovich|first=E. A.|year=1998|title=History of Civilisations of Central Asia|editor-last=Asimov|editor-first=M.S.|editor2-last=Bosworth|editor2-first=C.E.|volume=4 part I |chapter=Chapter 6 The Karakhanids |pages=119\u2013144|publisher=UNESCO Publishing|isbn=978-92-3-103467-1}}</ref> Harun died shortly afterwards, however, and the Samanids returned to Bukhara. In 999, Nasr b. Ali, a nephew of Harun, returned and took possession of Bukhara, meeting little resistance. The Samanid domains were split up between the [[Ghaznavids]], who gained [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] and [[Afghanistan]], and the Karakhanids, who received Transoxiana; the [[Oxus River]] thus became the boundary between the two rival empires.\n\n===Isma'il Muntasir's attempt to resurrect the Samanid state (1000\u20131005)===\n[[File:Isma'il Muntasir.jpg|thumb|270px|right|Artwork of [[Isma'il Muntasir]] in a battle.]]\n[[Isma'il Muntasir]] was the youngest son of Nuh II\u2014he was imprisoned by the Karakhanids after their conquest of Bukhara in 999. Some time later, Isma'il managed to escape to Khwarazm, where he gained support. Driving the Karakhanids out of Bukhara, he then moved on to and captured Samarkand. The approach of the Karakhanid army, however, forced Isma'il to give up all of his possessions, following which he travelled to Khorasan, where he captured Nishapur. Mahmud's army, however, made its way to the region, and Isma'il decided it necessary to flee again.\n\nIn 1003 Isma'il came back to Transoxiana, where he requested and received assistance from the Oghuz Turks of the [[Zarafshan]] valley. They defeated the Karakhanids in several battles, even when Nasr Khan was involved. For various reasons, however, Isma'il came to feel that he could not rely on the Oghuz to restore him, so he went back to Khorasan. He tried to gain Mahmud's support for a campaign to restore the Samanid state, but failed. Some time afterwards, he returned to the Zarafshan valley, where he gained the support of the Oghuz and others. A Karakhanid army was defeated in May 1004, but subsequently the Oghuz deserted Isma'il during another battle, and his army fell apart.\n\nFleeing to Khorasan yet again, Isma'il attempted to reenter Transoxiana in the end of 1004. The Karakhanids stopped this and Isma'il was nearly killed. Following this, he sought the hospitality of an [[Arab]] tribe near Merv. Their chief, however, killed Isma'il in 1005. His death marked the defeat of the last attempt to restore the Samanid state. Descendants of the Samanid family continued to live in Transoxiana where they were well regarded, but their power was relatively broken.\n\n===Iranian intermezzo===\nAlong with several other states, the Samanid Empire was part of the [[Iranian Intermezzo]], or \"Persian renaissance\". This period has been described as having a key importance in the formation of the Islamic civilization, both politically and culturally. In political terms, it saw an effective break up of the Abbasid power and the rise of several successor states such as the Samanids and Buyids while in cultural terms, it witnessed the rise of new Persian as an administrative and literary language.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OeiKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR19&dq=Medieval+Central+Asia+and+the+Persianate+World,+A.C.S.+Peacock,+D.G.+Tor,+Iranian+Intermezzo#v=onepage&q=Medieval%20Central%20Asia%20and%20the%20Persianate%20World,%20A.C.S.%20Peacock,%20D.G.%20Tor,%20Iranian%20Intermezzo&f=true|title=Medieval Central Asia and the Persianate World: Iranian Tradition and Islamic Civilisation|last=Peacock|first=A. C. S.|last2=Tor|first2=D. G.|date=2017-08-30|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=9780857727435|language=en|page=xix}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Government===\n\n====Structure====\n[[File:MansurISamanidCoinHistoryofIran.jpg|thumb|right|A Samanid coin minted in Bukhara bearing the name of [[Mansur I]] ]]\n\nThe system of the Samanid state was modelled after the Abbasid system,{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=143}} which in turn was modelled after the Sasanian system.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=146}}{{sfn|Shahbazi|2005}} The ruler of the state was the ''[[amir]]'', and the provinces were governed by appointed governors or local [[vassal]] rulers. The main responsibility of both governors and local rulers was to collect taxes and support the Samanid ruler with troops if needed. The most important province in the Samanid Empire was Khorasan, which was initially given to a relative of the Samanid ruler or a local Iranian prince (such as the [[Muhtajids]]), but was later given to one of his most trusted slaves. The governor of Khorasan was normally the ''[[sipah-salar]]'' (commander-in-chief).{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=143}}\n\nLike in the Abbasid Caliphate, Turkic slaves could rise to high office in the Samanid state, which would sometimes give them enough power to nearly make the ruler their puppet.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=143}}\n\n====The nature of political authority under the Samanids====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n===Cultural and religious efforts===\n\n\nThe Samanids revived [[Persian culture]] by patronizing [[Rudaki]],<ref>\"Mihragan\", J. Calmard, ''The Encyclopedia of Islam'', Vol.VII, Ed. C. E.Bosworth, E. van Donzel, W. P. Heinrichs and C. Pellat, (Brill, 1993), 18.</ref> [[Bal'ami]] and [[Daqiqi]].<ref>C.E. Bosworth, ''The Ghaznavids: 994\u20131040'', (Edinburgh University Press, 1963), 131.</ref> The Samanids determinedly propagated [[Sunni Islam]], and repressed [[Ismaili]] [[Shiism]]<ref>An Ismaili Heresiography: The \"Bab Al-Shaytan\" from Abu Tammam's Kitab Al ... By Wilferd Madelung, Paul Ernest Walker, pg. 5</ref> but were more tolerant of [[Twelver]] Shiism.<ref name=\"Elton L. Daniel pg. 74\"/> Islamic architecture and Islamo-Persian culture was spread deep into the heart of Central Asia by the Samanids. Following the first complete translation of the [[Qur'an]] into Persian, during the 9th century, populations under the Samanid empire began accepting Islam in significant numbers.<ref>Michael Dillon, ''Xinjiang: China's Muslim far Northwest'', (RoutledgeCurzon, 2004), 11.</ref>\n\nThrough zealous missionary work as many as 30,000 tents of [[Turkic peoples|Turks]] came to profess Islam and later under the Ghaznavids more than 55,000 under the [[Hanafi]] school of thought. The mass conversion of the Turks to Islam eventually led to a growing influence of the [[Ghaznavids]], who would later rule the region.\n\nAgriculture and trading were the economic bases of the Samanid State. The Samanids were heavily involved in trading&nbsp;\u2013 even with Europe, as thousands of Samanid coins that have been found in the Baltic and Scandinavian countries testify.<ref>History of Bukhara, By Narshakhi trans. Richard N. Frye, pg. 143</ref>\n\nAnother lasting contribution of the Samanids to the history of Islamic art is the pottery known as Samanid Epigraphic Ware: plates, bowls, and pitchers fired in a white slip and decorated only with calligraphy, often elegantly and rhythmically written.  The Arabic phrases used in this calligraphy are generally more or less generic well wishes, or Islamic admonitions to good table manners.\n\n===Scholarship===\n\n====Avicenna and Abu Rayhan al-Biruni====\n\n===Literature===\n[[File:The Sasanian King Khusraw and Courtiers in a Garden, Page from a manuscript of the Shahnama (Book of Kings) of Firdawsi, late 15th-early 16th century.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] king [[Khosrow II]] and his courtiers in a garden'', page from a manuscript of the [[Shahnameh]], late 15th-early 16th century. [[Brooklyn Museum]].]]\nIn the 9th and 10th centuries, there was a large amount of growth in literature, mostly in poetry. It was during the Samanid period that [[Persian literature]] appeared in Transoxiana and was formally recognized.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}} The advancement of an Islamic New Persian literature thus started in Transoxiana and Khorasan instead of [[Fars Province|Fars]], the homeland of the Persians. The best known poets of the Samanid period were [[Rudaki]] (d. 941), [[Daqiqi]] (d. 977) and [[Ferdowsi]] (d. 1020).{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}}\n\nAlthough Persian was the most-favored language, Arabic continued to enjoy a high status and was still popular among the members of the Samanid family.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}} For example, [[Al-Tha'\u0101lib\u012b|al-Tha'alibi]] wrote an Arabic anthology named Yatimat al-dahr (\"The Unique Pearl\"). The fourth section of the anthology included a detailed account of the poets that lived under the Samanids. It also states that the poets of Khwarazm mostly wrote in Arabic.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}}\n\nThe acknowledged founder of Persian classical poetry, and a man of great perception, was Rudaki, who was born in the village of [[Rudaki, Tajikistan|Panjrudak]], which is today part of the [[Panjakent District]] in [[Tajikistan]].{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}} Rudaki was already becoming popular during his early years, due to his poems, his voice, and his great skill in using the [[Chang (instrument)|chang]] (an Iranian instrument similar to the [[harp]]). He was shortly invited to the Samanid court, where he stayed almost the rest of his life. Fewer than 2,000 lines of his poetry have survived, but are enough to prove his great poetic skills\u2014he perfected every basic verse form of medieval Persian poetry: mathnawi, [[qasida]], [[ghazal]] and [[ruba'i]].{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}}\n\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\n\"Look at the cloud, how it cries like a grieving man\n: Thunder moans like a lover with a broken heart.\n: Now and then the sun peeks from behind the clouds\n: Like a prisoner hiding from the guard.\"&nbsp;\u2013 Rudaki\n</div>\n\nAnother prominent poet was [[Shahid Balkhi]], born in the village of Jakhudanak near Balkh. Not much is known about his life, but he is mentioned as being one of the best poets in the court of Nasr II, and one of the best scholars of the age. He was also a student of Rudaki, and had close relations with him. He died in 936, a few years before Rudaki's death. His death saddened Rudaki, who afterwards wrote an emotional [[elegy]] about him.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}}\n\nDaqiqi, who was a native of [[Tus, Iran|Tus]], began his career at the court of the [[Muhtajids|Muhtajid]] ruler [[Abu'l Muzaffar ibn Muhammad]] in [[Chaghaniyan]], and was later invited to the Samanid court.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}} Under the Samanids, a special interest arose in ancient Iranian legends and heroic traditions, thus inspiring Daqiqi to write the [[Shahnameh]] (\"The Book of Kings\"), a long [[epic poem]] based on the history of the Iranians. However, by his death in 977, he had only managed to complete a small part of it, which was about the conflict between [[Vishtaspa|Gushtasp]] and [[Arjasp]].{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}}\n\nHowever, the most prominent poet of that age was Ferdowsi, born in Tus in 940 to a ''dehqan'' family. It was during his youth that there was a period of growth under the Samanids. The rapid growth of interest in ancient Iranian history made him continue the work of Daqiqi, completing the Shahnameh in 994, only a few years before the fall of the Samanid Empire. He later completed a second version of the Shahnameh in 1010, which he presented to the Ghaznavid Sultan Mahmud. However, his work was not as appreciated by the Ghaznavids as it had been by the Samanids.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}}\n\n===Music===\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n===Population===\nUnder the Samanid Empire, the [[Zarafshan]] valley, [[Qashqadaryo Region|Kashka Darya]] and [[Usrushana]] were populated by [[Sogdia]]ns; [[Tukharistan]] by the Bactrians; [[Khwarezm]] by the Khwarazmians; the [[Fergana Valley|Ferghana valley]] by the Ferghanans; southern [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] by Khorasanians; and the [[Pamir mountains]] and environs by the [[Saka]] and other early Iranian peoples. All these groups were of Iranian ethnicity and spoke dialects of [[Middle Iranian]] and [[New Persian]]. In the words of Negmatov, \"they were the basis for the emergence and gradual consolidation of what became an Eastern Persian-Tajik ethnic identity.\"{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=101}}\n\n===Language===\nFerghana, Samarkand, and Bukhara were starting to be linguistically [[Persian language|Persianized]] in originally Khwarazmian and Sogdian areas during Samanid rule.<ref name=\"NourzhanovBleuer2013\">{{cite book|author1=Kirill Nourzhanov|author2=Christian Bleuer|title=Tajikistan: A Political and Social History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nR6oAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=8 October 2013|publisher=ANU E Press|isbn=978-1-925021-16-5|pages=30\u2013}}</ref> The Persian language spread and led to the extinction of Eastern Iranian languages like [[Bactrian language|Bactrian]] and [[Khwarezmian language|Khwarezmian]] with only a tiny amount of [[Sogdian language|Sogdian]]-descended [[Yaghnobi language|Yaghnobi]] speakers remaining among the now Persian-speaking Tajik population of Central Asia.  This was due to the fact that the Arab-Islamic army which invaded Central Asia also included some Persians who later governed the region like the Samanids.<ref name=\"Bergne2007\">{{cite book|author=Paul Bergne|title=The Birth of Tajikistan: National Identity and the Origins of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3coojMwTKU8C&pg=PA5#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 June 2007|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-283-7|pages=5\u2013}}</ref> Persian was rooted into Central Asia by the Samanids.<ref name=\"Paul Bergne 6\">{{cite book|author=Paul Bergne|title=The Birth of Tajikistan: National Identity and the Origins of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3coojMwTKU8C&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 June 2007|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-283-7|pages=6\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Intellectual life===\nIn the 9th and 10th centuries, intellectual life in Transoxiana and Khorasan reached a high level. In the words of N.N. Negmatov, \"It was inevitable that the local Samanid dynasty, seeking support among its literate classes, should cultivate and promote local cultural traditions, literacy and literature.\"{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=93}}\n\nThe main Samanid towns&nbsp;\u2013 [[Bukhara]], [[Samarkand]], [[Balkh]], [[Merv]], [[Nishapur]], [[Khujand]], [[Bunjikath]], [[Hulbuk]], [[Termez]] and others, became the major cultural centres under the state. Scholars, poets, artists and other men of education from many Muslim countries assembled in the Samanid capital of Bukhara, where a rich soil was created for the prosper of creative thought, thus making it one of the most distinguished cultural centres of the Eastern world. An outstanding library known as ''Siw\u0101n al-hikma'' (\"Storehouse of Wisdom\") was put together in Bukhara, known for its various types of books.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=94}}\n\n=== Arts ===\n[[File:Two Bowls with Figures and a Footed Plate with Birds MET DP258911.jpg|thumb|Example of figural earthenware ceramics from Samanid period.]]\n\n==== Crafts ====\n[[File:Bowl with Arabic Inscription.jpg|thumb|Bowl with Arabic Inscription]]\nDue to extensive excavations at [[Nishapur]], Iran, in the mid-twentieth century, Samanid pottery is well-represented in Islamic art collections around the world. These ceramics are largely made from [[earthenware]] and feature either calligraphic inscriptions of Arabic proverbs, or colorful figural decorations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grube|first=Ernst J.|date=February 1965|title=The Art of Islamic Pottery|journal=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Bulletin|volume=23|issue=6|pages=209\u2013228|doi=10.2307/3258167|issn=0026-1521|jstor=3258167}}</ref> The Arabic proverbs often speak to the values of \"Adab\" culture\u2014hospitality, generosity, and modesty.<ref>Pancaroglu, Oya. \"Serving wisdom: The contents of Samanid epigraphic pottery.\" Studies in Islamic and Later Indian Art from the Arthur M. Sackler Museum, Harvard University Art Museum (2002): 58-68.</ref>\n\nThe bowl with the Arabic inscription shown here is from Iran, during the Samanid period in the 10th century. It has a white slip with black slip decoration under a transparent glaze. There is calligraphic decoration all around the bowl. It is elongated at some points and compressed in other areas of the letter to the point where it almost looks abstract. Right in the center of the bowl is a black dot. If the bowl is looked at closely there are cracks and marks that have occurred over time. What would once have been a white bowl is now stained yellow in some areas. The calligraphy looks well thought out and planned. Each letter is well spaced, and the whole saying fits perfectly around the bowl. This may be because the artists used to practice beforehand on paper. The saying translates to \u201cPlanning before work protects you from regret; prosperity and peace\u201d\n\n===Economy===\n\n====Agriculture====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n====Mining====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}<br />\n\n====Material culture====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n====Domestic and external trade====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Legacy==\n\nIn commending the Samanids, the epic Persian poet [[Ferdowsi]] says of them:\n\n<blockquote>\n\u06a9\u062c\u0627 \u0622\u0646 \u0628\u0632\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0646 \u0633\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646<br/>\n\u0632 \u0628\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u062a\u0627 \u0628\u0647 \u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646\n</blockquote>\n\n\"Where have all the great [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanians]] gone?<br/>\nFrom the [[Bahram V of Persia|Bahr\u0101mids]] to the Samanids what has come upon?\"\n\nA Bukharian historian writing in 943 stated that [[Ismail Samani]]: <blockquote>was indeed worthy and right for [[padishah]]ship. He was an intelligent, just, compassionate person, one possessing reason and prescience...he conducted affairs with justice and good ethics.  Whoever tyrannized people he would punish...In affairs of state he was always impartial.<ref>Edward Allworth, ''The Modern Uzbeks: from the fourteenth century to the present : a cultural history'', p. 19</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe celebrated scholar [[Nizam al-Mulk]], in his famous work ''[[Siyasatnama]]'', stated that Ismail Samani: <blockquote>was extremely just, and his good qualities were many.  He had pure faith in God (to Him be power and glory) and he was generous to the poor&nbsp;\u2013 to name only one of his notable virtues.<ref>''The book of government, or, Rules for kings: the Siyar al-Muluk'', or, ''Siyasat-nama of Nizam al-Mulk'', tr. Hubert Darke, p. 14</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe [[Somoni]] currency of [[Tajikistan]] is named after the Samanids.  A notable airline based in [[Dushanbe]] is also named [[Somon Air]]. Also, the highest mountain in Tajikistan and in the former [[Soviet Union]] is named after Ismail Samani.<ref>[[Richard Foltz]], ''A History of the Tajiks: Iranians of the East'', London: Bloomsbury, 2019, p. 68.</ref> The mountain was formerly known as \"Stalin Peak\" and \"Communism Peak\" but in 1998 the name was officially changed to [[Ismoil Somoni Peak]].\n\n==Samanid rulers==\n{|style=\"width:100%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:17%;\"| Bukhara\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:17%;\"| Samarkand\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:17%;\"| Ferghana\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:15%;\"| Shash\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:15%;\"| Herat\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Saman Khuda]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u062e\u062f\u0627}}<br/> <small>(A Persian landowner from the village of Saman in [[Balkh]] province in northern [[Afghanistan]], he arrived in [[Merv]] to the court of the [[Umayyad]] governor of Khorasan, [[Asad ibn Abdallah al-Qasri]], under whose influence he became a Muslim and served the governor till his death. He was the founder of the Samanid dynasty)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Asad ibn Saman]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u0633\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646}}<br/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Nuh ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0646\u0648\u062d \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013841/2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ahmad ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013864/5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Yahya ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u06cc\u062d\u06cc\u06cc\u0670 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013855\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ilyas ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0633 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013856\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ahmad ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013864/5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ibrahim ibn Ilyas]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0633}}<br/>856\u2013867\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Isma'il ibn Ahmad|Abu Ibrahim Isma'il ibn Ahmad]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>892\u2013907\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Nasr I]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0646\u0635\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>864\u2013892\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ya'qub ibn Ahmad]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u06cc\u0639\u0642\u0648\u0628 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>?\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Saffarids]]<br/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Isma'il ibn Ahmad|Abu Ibrahim Isma'il ibn Ahmad]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>892\u2013907\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ahmad Samani|Ahmad ibn Isma'il]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644}}<br/>907\u2013914\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Nasr II]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0648\u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u0646 \u0646\u0635\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>914\u2013943\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Nuh I]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0646\u0648\u062d \u0628\u0646 \u0646\u0635\u0631}}<br/>943\u2013954\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ibrahim ibn Ahmad]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>947\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Abd al-Malik I (Samanid emir)|Abd al-Malik ibn Nuh I]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0644\u06a9 \u0628\u0646 \u0646\u0648\u062d}}<br/>954\u2013961\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Mansur I|Abu Salih Mansur ibn Nuh I]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0635\u0627\u0644\u062d \u0645\u0646\u0635\u0648\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0646\u0648\u062d}}<br/>961\u2013976\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Nuh II|Nuh ibn Mansur]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0646\u0648\u062d \u0628\u0646 \u0645\u0646\u0635\u0648\u0631}}<br/>976\u2013997\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Abd al-Aziz ibn Nuh|Abd al-Aziz]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0639\u0632\u06cc\u0632}}<br/>992\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Mansur II|Abu'l-Harith Mansur ibn Nuh II]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0627\u0631\u062b \u0645\u0646\u0635\u0648\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0646\u0648\u062d}}<br/>997\u2013999\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Abd al-Malik II (Samanid emir)|Abd al-Malik ibn Nuh II]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0639\u0628\u062f\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0627\u0644\u06a9 \u0628\u0646 \u0646\u0648\u062d}}<br/> 999\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Isma'il Muntasir|Isma'il Muntasir ibn Nuh II]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644 \u0645\u0646\u062a\u0635\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0646\u0648\u062d}}<br/>1000&nbsp;\u2013 1005\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n|-\n| colspan=\"6\" align=\"center\" | ?\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Iranian Intermezzo]]\n*[[List of Iranian dynasties and countries]]\n*[[List of kings of Persia|List of kings of Iran]]\n*[[List of Sunni Muslim dynasties]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{commons category|Samanid empire|Samanid Empire}}\n*{{cite journal|title=The Development of Persian Culture under the Early Ghaznavids |first=C.E. |last=Bosworth |journal=Iran |volume= 6 |pages=33\u201344 |year=1968 |ref=harv|doi=10.2307/4299599 |jstor=4299599 }}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | article = \u0100L-E MO\u1e24T\u0100J | last = Bosworth | first = C. Edmund | authorlink =  | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/al-e-mohtaj-a-local-dynasty | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica, Vol. I, Fasc. 7 | pages = 764\u2013766 | location = London et al. | publisher = C. Edmund Bosworth | year = 1984 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite encyclopedia | article = A\u1e24MAD B. SAHL B. H\u0100\u0160EM | last = Bosworth | first = C. Edmund | authorlink =  | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ahmad-b-14 | editor-last = | editor-first =  | editor-link = | encyclopedia  = Encyclopaedia Iranica, Vol. I, Fasc. 6 | pages = 643\u2013644 | location = London et al. | publisher = C. Edmund Bosworth | year = 1984 | isbn = |ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Bosworth | first = C. Edmund | authorlink = | chapter = | title = The Ornament of Histories: A History of the Eastern Islamic Lands AD 650\u20131041: The Persian Text of Abu Sa'id 'Abd Al-Hayy Gardizi | year = 2011 | publisher = I.B.Tauris | location= | url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=VG36ym3H3CQC&dq=false | editor-first = | editor-last = | isbn = 9781848853539| pages=1\u2013169}}\n* Daniel, Elton. (2001) ''The History of Iran'' (The Greenwood Histories of the Modern Nations) Westport, CT: Greenwood Press. {{ISBN|0-313-30731-8}}, {{ISBN|978-0-313-30731-7}}\n* [[Richard Foltz|Foltz, Richard]], ''A History of the Tajiks: Iranians of the East'', London: [[Bloomsbury]], 2019.\n* {{cite book | title = The Cambridge History of Iran, Volume 4: From the Arab Invasion to the Saljuqs | year = 1975 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge | editor-last = Frye | editor-first = R. N. | last = Frye | first = R. N. | authorlink = Richard N. Frye | chapter = The S\u0101m\u0101nids | pages = 136\u2013161 | isbn = 978-0-521-20093-6 | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=hvx9jq_2L3EC&pg=PA136 | ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book | last = Houtsma | first = M. Th | authorlink =  | chapter = | title = First Encyclopaedia of Islam: 1913\u20131936 | year = 1993 | publisher = Brill | location= | url=https://books.google.dk/books?id=fWNpIGNFz0IC&dq=false | editor-first = | editor-last = | isbn = 9789004097964 | pages=579\u20131203}}\n* {{cite book | title = History of Civilizations of Central Asia: Age of Achievement, A.D. 750 to the end of the 15th-century | year = 1998 | publisher = UNESCO | location = | editor-last = | editor-first = | last = B. A. Litvinsky | first = Ahmad Hasan Dani | authorlink = | chapter = | isbn = 9789231032110 | url = https://books.google.dk/books?id=18eABeokpjEC&dq= |ref=harv}}*{{cite encyclopedia | last = Shahbazi | first  = A. Shapur | title = SASANIAN DYNASTY | url = http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/sasanian-dynasty | year = 2005 | encyclopedia = Encyclopaedia Iranica, Online Edition | accessdate = 23 January 2016|ref=harv}}\n\n{{Samanid Rulers}}\n{{Samanid Provinces}}\n{{Iran topics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Samanid Empire| ]]\n[[Category:Former countries in Western Asia]]\n[[Category:Sunni dynasties]]\n[[Category:Tabaristan]]\n[[Category:9th century in Iran]]\n[[Category:10th century in Iran]]\n[[Category:Iranian empires]]\n[[Category:Medieval Khorasan]]\n[[Category:819 establishments]]\n[[Category:999 disestablishments]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in the 810s]]\n[[Category:States and territories disestablished in the 990s]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Iranian empire ruled by the Samanids}}\n{{Infobox country\n|native_name            = \u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646\n|conventional_long_name = Samanid Empire\n|common_name            = Samanid Empire\n|era                    = [[Middle Ages]]\n|status                 = Empire\n|status_text            =\n|empire                 =\n|government_type        = Emirate\n|year_start             = 819\n|year_end               = 999\n|event_start            =\n|date_start             =\n|event_end              =\n|date_end               =\n|p1                     = Saffarid dynasty\n|flag_p1                = Saffarid dynasty 861-1003.png\n|p2                     = Abbasid Caliphate\n|flag_p2                = Abbasids850.png\n|p3                     = Alid dynasties of northern Iran\n|flag_p3                = Alavids-map.png\n|p4                     = Banijurids\n|flag_p4                =\n|p5                     = Bukhar Khudahs\n|flag_p5                =\n|p6                     = Principality of Ushrusana\n|flag_p6                =\n|p7                     = Principality of Farghana\n|flag_p7                =\n|p8                     = Sogdia\n|image_p8               = [[Image:TarkhunSogdianCoin.jpg|25px]]\n|s1                     = Ghaznavid dynasty\n|flag_s1                = Ghaznavid Empire 975 - 1187 (AD).PNG\n|s2                     = Karakhanids\n|flag_s2                = KaraKhanidAD1000.png\n|s3                     = Banu Ilyas\n|flag_s3                = BanuIlyasMapHistoryofIran.png\n|s4                     = Farighunids\n|flag_s4                =\n|s5                     = Muhtajids\n|flag_s5                =\n|s6                     = Buyid dynasty\n|flag_s6                =\n|image_flag             =\n|flag                   =\n|flag_type              =\n|image_coat             =\n|image_map              = Samanid dynasty (819\u2013999).GIF\n|image_map_caption      = The Samanid Empire at its greatest extent under [[Ismail Samani]]\n|capital                = {{plainlist|\n* [[Samarkand]] {{small|(819\u2013892)}}\n* [[Bukhara]] {{small|(892\u2013999)}}\n}}\n|common_languages       = {{plainlist|\n*[[Persian language|Persian]] ({{small|[[lingua franca]], court, academia}}),<ref>\"Persian Prose Literature.\" World Eras. 2002. HighBeam Research. (September 3, 2012);\"''Princes, although they were often tutored in Arabic and religious subjects, frequently did not feel as comfortable with the Arabic language and preferred literature in Persian, which was either their mother tongue\u2014as in the case of dynasties such as the Saffarids (861\u20131003), Samanids (873\u20131005), and Buyids (945\u20131055)...''\". [https://web.archive.org/web/20130502180821/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G2-3034700041.html]</ref><ref>Elton L. Daniel, ''History of Iran'', (Greenwood Press, 2001), 74.</ref>{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=146}}<ref name=\"Paul Bergne 6\">{{cite book|author=Paul Bergne|title=The Birth of Tajikistan: National Identity and the Origins of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3coojMwTKU8C&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 June 2007|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-283-7|pages=6\u2013}}</ref>\n*[[Arabic]] ({{small|theology}}){{sfn|Frye|1975|p=145}}\n}}\n|religion               = [[Sunni Islam]] ({{small|minority [[Shia Islam]], [[Nestorian Christianity|Nestorianism]], [[Zoroastrianism]]}})\n|currency               =\n|leader1                = [[Ahmad ibn Asad]]\n|leader2                = [[Abd al-Malik II (Samanid emir)|'Abd al-Malik II]]\n|year_leader1           = 819\u2013864/5\n|year_leader2           = 999\n|title_leader           = [[Emir]]\n|stat_year1   = 928 est.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Turchin|first1=Peter|last2=Adams|first2=Jonathan M.|last3=Hall|first3=Thomas D | title = East-West Orientation of Historical Empires | journal = Journal of World-systems Research|date=December 2006 |volume=12|issue=2 |page=222 |url =http://jwsr.pitt.edu/ojs/index.php/jwsr/article/view/369/381|accessdate=12 September 2016 |issn= 1076-156X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taagepera|first=Rein|year=1997|title=Expansion and Contraction Patterns of Large Polities: Context for Russia|journal=International Studies Quarterly|volume=41|issue=3|pages=475\u2013504|doi=10.1111/0020-8833.00053|jstor=2600793|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/3cn68807}}</ref>\n|stat_area1   = 2850000\n}}\n{{History of Iran}}\nThe '''Samanid Empire''' ({{lang-fa|\u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646}}, ''S\u0101m\u0101niy\u0101n'', also known as the '''Samanian Empire''', '''Samanid dynasty''', '''Samanid Emirate''', or simply '''Samanids''') was a [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]]{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=151}} [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] empire{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=164}} from 819 to 999. The empire was centered in [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] and [[Transoxiana]] during its existence; at its greatest extent, the empire encompassed all of today's [[Afghanistan]], large parts of [[Iran]], [[Tajikistan]], [[Turkmenistan]], [[Uzbekistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], and parts of [[Kazakhstan]] and [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Taagepera|first=Rein|date=1997-01-01|title=Expansion and Contraction Patterns of Large Polities: Context for Russia|jstor=2600793|journal=International Studies Quarterly|volume=41|issue=3|pages=475\u2013504|doi=10.1111/0020-8833.00053|url=https://escholarship.org/uc/item/3cn68807}}</ref>\n\nThe Samanid state was founded by four brothers; [[Nuh ibn Asad|Nuh]], [[Ahmad ibn Asad|Ahmad]], [[Yahya ibn Asad|Yahya]], and [[Ilyas ibn Asad|Ilyas]]\u2014each of them ruled their own territory under Abbasid suzerainty. In 892, [[Ismail Samani]] (892\u2013907) united the Samanid state under one ruler, thus effectively putting an end to the [[feudal]] system used by the Samanids. It was also under him that the Samanids became independent of Abbasid authority.\n\nThe Samanid Empire is part of the [[Iranian Intermezzo]], which saw the creation of a [[Persianate society|Persianate]] culture and identity that brought Iranian speech and traditions into the fold of the [[Muslim world|Islamic world]]. This would later lead to the formation of the [[Turko-Persian tradition|Turko-Persian]] culture.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Turko-Persia in Historical Perspective|last = Canfield L.|first = Robert|publisher = Cambridge University Press|year = 2002|isbn = 9780521522915|location = |pages = 12 }}</ref>\n\nThe Samanids promoted the arts, giving rise to the advancement of science and literature, and thus attracted scholars such as [[Rudaki]], [[Ferdowsi]], and [[Avicenna]]. While under Samanid control, [[Bukhara]] was a rival to [[Baghdad]] in its glory.<ref name=\"Elton L. Daniel pg. 74\">''The History of Iran'' by Elton L. Daniel, pg. 74</ref> Scholars note that the Samanids revived [[Persian language]] and culture more than the [[Buyids]] and the Saffarids, while continuing to patronize [[Arabic]] for sciences as well as the religious studies. They considered themselves to be descendants of the [[Sasanian Empire]].{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=145-146}}<ref name=\"Elton L. Daniel pg. 74\"/> In a famous edict, Samanid authorities declared that \"here, in this region, the language is [[Persian language|Persian]], and the kings of this realm are Persian kings.\"<ref name=\"Elton L. Daniel pg. 74\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Origins===\nThe eponymous ancestor of the Samanid dynasty was [[Saman Khuda]], a [[Persian people|Persian]] noble who belonged to a ''[[dehqan]]'' family, which was a class of land-owning magnates. The original home of the Samanids is unclear, for some [[Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] texts claim that the name was derived from a village near [[Samarkand]], while others assert it was a village near [[Balkh]] or [[Termez|Tirmidh]]. The latter is more probable since the earliest appearance of the Samanid family appears to be in [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] rather than [[Transoxiana]].<ref name=\"The Cambridge History of Iran\">{{cite book|last1=Frye|first1=Richard N.|title=The Cambridge History of Iran|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=136}}</ref> In some sources the Samanids claimed to be descended from the noble [[House of Mihran|Mihran family]] of [[Bahram Chobin]], whereas one author claimed that they belonged to the Turkish Oghuz tribe, although this is most unlikely.<ref name=\"The Cambridge History of Iran\"/> Originally a [[Zoroastrian]], Saman Khuda converted to [[Islam]] during the governorship of [[Asad ibn Abdallah al-Qasri]] in [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]],{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=136}} and named his oldest son as [[Asad ibn Saman|Asad]] in the governor's honour.{{sfn|Gibb|1986|p=685}} In 819, the governor of Khorasan, [[Ghassan ibn Abbad]], rewarded the four sons of Asad for their aid against the rebel [[Rafi ibn al-Layth]]; [[Nuh ibn Asad|Nuh]] received [[Samarkand]]; [[Ahmad ibn Asad|Ahmad]] received [[Farghana]]; [[Yahya ibn Asad|Yahya]] received [[Tashkent|Shash]]; and [[Ilyas ibn Asad|Ilyas]] received [[Herat]].{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=136}} This marked the beginning of the Samanid dynasty.\n\n===Rise===\n\n====The Samanid branch in Herat (819\u2013857)====\n\nIlyas died in 856, and was succeeded by his son [[Ibrahim ibn Ilyas]]\u2014the [[Tahirid dynasty|Tahirid]] governor of Khorasan, [[Muhammad ibn Tahir]], thereafter appointed him as the commander of his army, and sent him on an expedition against the [[Saffarid dynasty|Saffarid]] ruler [[Ya'qub ibn al-Layth al-Saffar]] in [[Sistan]]. He was defeated at a battle near [[Pushang]] in 857, and fled to [[Nishapur]], where he was captured by Ya'qub al-Saffar and sent to Sistan as a hostage.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=136}} The Tahirids thereafter assumed direct control over Herat.\n\n====The Samanid branches in Transoxiana (819\u2013892)====\n{{See Also|Samanid Civil War of 888}}\n[[File:Transoxiana 8th century.svg|thumb|right|300px|Map of [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] and [[Transoxiana]].]]\nIn 839/40, Nuh seized [[Isfijab]] from the nomadic [[Paganism|pagan]] [[Oghuz Turks|Turks]] living in the [[steppe]]. He thereafter had a wall constructed around the city to protect it from their attacks. He died in 841/2\u2014his two brothers Yahya and Ahmad were then appointed as the joint rulers of the city by the Tahirid governor of Khorasan.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=136}} After Yahya's death in 855, Ahmad took control over Ch\u00e2ch, thus becoming the ruler of most of [[Transoxiana]]. He died in 864/5; his son [[Nasr I]] received Farghana and Samarkand, while his other son [[Ya'qub ibn Ahmad|Ya'qub]] received Ch\u00e2ch (areas around modern Tashkent/Chachkent).{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=137}} Meanwhile, the Tahirids' authority had significantly weakened after suffering several defeats by the Saffarid ruler Ya'qub al-Saffar, thus losing their grip over the Samanids, who became more or less independent. Nasr I used this opportunity to strengthen his authority by sending his brother [[Ismail Samani|Ismail]] to [[Bukhara]], which was in an unstable condition after suffering from raids by the [[Afrighids|Afrighid dynasty]] of [[Khwarazm]]. When Ismail reached the city, he was warmly received by its inhabitants, who saw him as one who could restore order.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=137}} Regardless, the [[Bukhar Khudahs]] continued to autonomously rule in Bukhara for a few more years.\n\nAfter not so long, disagreement over where tax money should be distributed started a conflict between the brothers. Ismail was eventually victorious in the dynastic struggle, and took control of the Samanid state. However, Nasr had been the one who had been invested with Transoxiana, and the Abbasid [[caliph]]s continued to recognize him as the rightful ruler. Because of this, Ismail continued to recognize his brother as well, but Nasr was completely powerless, a situation that would continue until his death in August 892.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=137}}\n\n===Final unification and height of power (892\u2013907)===\n[[File:13 Buhara Mavzolej Ismaila Samanija (2).JPG|thumb|right|300px|Picture of the [[Samanid Mausoleum]], the burial site of [[Ismail Samani]].]]\nA few months later, Ya'qub al-Saffar also died and was succeeded by his brother [[Amr ibn al-Layth]], who saw himself as the heir of the Tahirids, thus claiming Transoxiana, Khorasan and other parts of Iran for himself. He thereafter forced the Abbasid caliph to recognize him as the ruler of those territories. In the spring of 900, he [[Battle of Balkh|clashed]] with Ismail near [[Balkh]], but was defeated and taken to captivity. Ismail thereafter sent him Baghdad, where he was executed.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=138}} Ismail was thereafter recognized as the ruler of all of Khorasan and Transoxiana by the caliph.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=138}} Furthermore, he also received the investiture over [[Tabaristan]], [[Ray, Iran|Ray]] and [[Isfahan]].{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=138}} It was also during this period that the Afrighid dynasty was forced into submission.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=138}}\n\nBefore his major victory against the Saffarids, he had made various expeditions in Transoxiana; in 892, he put an end to the [[Principality of Ushrusana]] by seizing all of its lands. During the same period, he put an end to the Bukhar Khudas in Bukhara. In 893, he invaded the territories of the [[Karluk Turks]], taking [[Taraz|Talas]] and converting the [[Church of the East|Nestorian church]] there into a [[mosque]].<ref>Renee Grousset, ''The Empire of the Steppes:A History of Central Asia'', Transl. Naomi Walford, (Rutgers University Press, 1991), 142.</ref><ref>\"Samanids\", C. E. Bosworth, ''The Encyclopedia of Islam'', Vol. VIII, Ed. C. E. Bosworth, E. van Donzel, W.P. Heinrichs and G. Lecomte, (E.J. Brill, 1995), 1026.</ref>\n\nIn 900, Ismail sent an army under [[Muhammad ibn Harun al-Sarakhsi]] against [[Muhammad ibn Zayd]], the [[Alid dynasties of northern Iran|Zaydi]] ruler of Tabaristan and [[Gorgan]]. The invasion was successful; Muhammad ibn Zayd was killed and Tabaristan was conquered by the Samanids. However, Muhammad ibn Harun shortly revolted, forcing Ismail himself to invade the region the following year. Muhammad ibn Harun thereafter fled to [[Daylam]], while Ismail reconquered Tabaristan and Gorgan.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=140}} In 901, [[Amr ibn al-Layth|Amr Saffari]] was defeated at the battle of Balkh by the Samanids, which reduced the Saffarid dynasty to a minor tributary in Sistan.{{sfn|Bosworth|1968|p=35}} It was during this period that the Samanids were at their height of power, ruling as far as [[Qazvin]] in the west<ref name=\"iranicaonline.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/esmail-b-ahmad-b-asad-samani |title=ESM\u0100\u02bf\u012aL, b. A\u1e25mad b. Asad S\u0100M\u0100N\u012a, AB\u016a EBR\u0100H\u012aM |last1=Bosworth |first1=C. Edmund |authorlink1=Clifford Edmund Bosworth |date=15 December 1998 |website=Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica |accessdate=24 January 2015}}</ref> and [[Peshawar]] in the east.\n\nIsmail is known in history as a competent general and a strong ruler; many stories about him are written in Arabic and Persian sources. Furthermore, because of his campaigns in the north, his empire was so safe from enemy incursions that the defences of Bukhara and Samarkand went unused. However, this later had consequences; at the end of the dynasty, the walls--earlier strong, but now falling apart--were greatly missed by the Samanids, who were constantly under attack by the [[Karakhanids]] and other enemies.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=140}}\n\nIsmail died in November 907, and was succeeded by his son [[Ahmad Samani]] (r. 907\u2013914).\n\n===Intermediate period (907\u2013961)===\nNot long after his accession, Ahmad invaded Sistan; by 911, Sistan was under complete Samanid control, and Ahmad's cousin [[Abu Salih Mansur]] was appointed as its governor. Meanwhile, an [[Alids|Alid]] named [[Hasan al-Utrush]] was slowly re-establishing Zaydi over Tabaristan. In 913, Ahmad sent an army under [[Muhammad ibn Sa'luk]] to deal with him. Although the Samanid army was much larger, Hasan managed to emerge victorious. Ahmad, before he could plan another expedition to Tabaristan, was the following year murdered by some of his slaves in a tent near Bukhara.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=141}} During his reign, Ahmad is also said to have replaced the language of the court from Persian to [[Arabic]], which made him unpopular among his subjects, and forced him to change it back to Persian. After Ahmad's death, his eight-year-old son [[Nasr II]] (r. 914\u2013943) succeeded him.\n[[File:NasrIISamanidCoinHistoryofIran.jpg|thumb|right|Coin of [[Nasr II]], minted in [[Nishapur]] (933/4).]]\nDue to Nasr's youth, his prime minister [[Abu 'Abd-Allah al-Jaihani]] took care over most of the state affairs. Jaihani was not only an experienced administrator, but also a prominent geographer and greatly educated man. Almost right after Nasr II had ascended the throne, several revolts erupted, the most dangerous one being under his paternal grand-uncle, [[Ishaq ibn Ahmad]], who seized Samarkand and began minting coins there, while his son Abu Salih Mansur seized [[Nishapur]] and several cities in Khorasan. Ishaq was eventually defeated and captured, while Abu Salih Mansur died of natural causes in 915.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=141}} Some time later Nasr II once again had to deal with rebels; in 919, the governor of Khorasan, [[Husayn ibn Ali Marvarrudhi]], rebelled against Samanid authority. Nasr responded by sending an army under [[Ahmad ibn Sahl]] to suppress the rebellion, which the latter managed to accomplish. After a few weeks, however, Ahmad shortly rebelled himself at Nishapur, made incursions into Gorgan, and then fortified himself in [[Merv]] to avoid a Samanid counter-attack. Nevertheless, the Samanid general [[Hamuya ibn Ali]] managed to lure Ahmad out of Merv, and defeated him in a battle at [[Marw al-Rudh]]; he was captured and imprisoned in Bukhara, where he remained until his death in 920.\n\nIn the west, Nasr II clashed several times with [[Daylamite]] and [[Gilaki people|Gilite]] rulers; In 921, the Zaydids under the Gilite ruler [[Lili ibn al-Nu'man]] invaded Khorasan, but were defeated by the [[Simjurids|Simjurid]] general [[Simjur al-Dawati]]. Later in 930, a Dailamite military leader, [[Makan ibn Kaki]], seized Tabaristan and Gurgan, and even took possession of Nishapur in western Khorasan. He was, however, forced to withdraw back to Tabaristan one year later, due to the threat that Samanids posed.<ref name=\"EI2-164\">Nazim (1987), p. 164</ref><ref>Madelung (1975), pp. 211\u2013212</ref> Makan then returned to Tabaristan, where he was defeated by the [[Ziyarid]] ruler [[Mardavij]], who managed to conquer the region.<ref name=\"EI2-164\">Nazim (1987), p. 164</ref><ref name=\"Iran212\">Madelung (1975), p. 212</ref> In 935, Nasr II re-established Samanid control in Gurgan and made Mardavij's successor [[Vushmgir]] his vassal. However, in 939 he declared independence, but was defeated the following year at [[Battle of Iskhabad|Iskhabad]].\n\nIn 943 several Samanid army officers, angry at Nasr's support of [[Isma'ili]] missionaries, formed a conspiracy to murder him. Nasr's son [[Nuh I]], however, learned of the conspiracy. He went to a banquet designed to organize the plot and had the head of their leader cut off. To appease the other officers, he promised to stop the Isma'ili missionaries from continuing their activities. He then convinced his father to abdicate, who died of [[tuberculosis]] after a few months.<ref>''A new text on Ismailism at the Samanid court'', Patricia Crone and Luke Treadwell, '''Texts, documents, and artefacts:Islamic Studies in Honour of D.S. Richards''', ed. Chase F. Robinson, (Brill, 2003), 46.</ref>\n\nRight when Nuh I ascended the throne, a revolt erupted in Khwarazm, which he managed to suppress. Later in 945, he had to deal with the [[Muhtajids|Muhtajid]] ruler [[Abu 'Ali Chaghani]], who refused to relinquish his post as governor of Khorasan to [[Ibrahim ibn Simjur]]. Abu 'Ali Chaghani then rebelled, and was joined by several prominent figures such as [[Abu Mansur Muhammad]], whom he appointed as his commander-in-chief. In 947, he installed Nuh's uncle [[Ibrahim ibn Ahmad]] as ''amir'' in Bukhara. Abu 'Ali Chaghani then returned to his domains in [[Chaghaniyan]]. Ibrahim, however, was unpopular with the people of Bukhara, and Nuh soon retaliated by retaking the city and blinding Ibrahim and two brothers.\n\nWhen Abu Ali Chaghani received the news of the re-capture of Bukhara, he once again marched towards it, but was defeated by an army sent by Nuh and withdrew back to Chaghaniyan. After some time, he left the region and tried to obtain support from other Samanid vassals. Meanwhile, Nuh had Chaghaniyan ravaged{{sfn|Bosworth|2011|p=63}} and its capital sacked.{{sfn|Frye|1975|pp=149\u2013151}} Another battle shortly ensued between Abu 'Ali Chaghani and a Samanid army in [[Tukharistan]], which resulted in a Samanid victory. Fortunately for Abu Ali Chaghani, he managed to secure the support of other Samanid vassals, such as the rulers of [[Khuttal]], and the Kumiji [[mountain people]], but in the end made peace with Nuh, who allowed him to keep Chaghaniyan in return for sending his son [[Abu'l Muzaffar Abdallah]] as hostage to Bukhara.{{sfn|Bosworth|2011|p=63}}{{sfn|Bosworth|1984|pp=764\u2013766}}\n[[File:Iran circa 1000AD.png|thumb|right|250px|[[Iran]] in the mid-10th century.]]\n[[Alp Tigin]], nominal vassal of the Samanids, conquered Ghazna in 962 from the Lawik dynasty.<ref>He dispossessed an indigenous family who had ruled in [[Ghazni]], the Lawiks (?), and following him a series of slave commanders, ruled there as nominal vassals of the Samanids; they struck coins but placed the names of the Samanids on them</ref><ref>Gard\u012bz\u012b, ed. \u1e24ab\u012bb\u012b, pp. 161\u201362; J\u016bzj\u0101n\u012b, \u1e6cabaq\u0101t, I, pp. 226\u201327; Ne\u1e93\u0101m-al-Molk, pp. 142\u201358; \u0160ab\u0101nk\u0101ra\u02be\u012b, pp. 29\u201334; Bosworth, 1965, pp. 16\u201321</ref> The fifth of these commanders was Seb\u00fcktigin, who governed \u1e20azna for twenty years till 387 AH/997 CE with the title (as it appears from his tomb inscription<ref>Flury, pp. 62\u201363</ref>) of al-\u1e25\u0101jeb al-ajall (most noble commander). He would later be the founder of an independent dynasty based in Ghazna, following the decline of the Samanid Empire in the 990s.<ref>[http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/ghaznavids \"GHAZNAVIDS\"] ''[[Encyclop\u00e6dia Iranica]]''. Retrieved 17 August 2014</ref>\n\n===Decline and fall (961\u2013999)===\nThe power of the Samanids began to crumble in the latter half of the 10th century. In 962, one the [[Ghilman|ghulams]], [[Alp Tigin]], commander of the army in Khorasan, seized [[Ghazna]] and established himself there.<ref name=\"sinor\">{{citation |year=1990|title=The Cambridge History of Early Inner Asia|editor-last=Sinor|editor-first=Denis|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521243049}}</ref> His successors, however, including [[Seb\u00fck Tigin]], continued to rule as Samanid \"governors\". With the weakened Samanids facing rising challenges from the [[Karakhanid]]s for control of [[Transoxiana]], Seb\u00fck later took control of all the provinces south of the Oxus and established the [[Ghaznavids|Ghaznavid Empire]].\n\nIn 992, a [[Kara-Khanid dynasty|Karakhanid]], Harun Bughra Khan, grandson of the paramount tribal chief of the [[Karluks|Karluk]] confederation [[Sultan Satuq Bughra Khan]], captured [[Bukhara]], the Samanid capital.<ref name=\"UNESCO\">{{citation|last=Davidovich|first=E. A.|year=1998|title=History of Civilisations of Central Asia|editor-last=Asimov|editor-first=M.S.|editor2-last=Bosworth|editor2-first=C.E.|volume=4 part I |chapter=Chapter 6 The Karakhanids |pages=119\u2013144|publisher=UNESCO Publishing|isbn=978-92-3-103467-1}}</ref> Harun died shortly afterwards, however, and the Samanids returned to Bukhara. In 999, Nasr b. Ali, a nephew of Harun, returned and took possession of Bukhara, meeting little resistance. The Samanid domains were split up between the [[Ghaznavids]], who gained [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] and [[Afghanistan]], and the Karakhanids, who received Transoxiana; the [[Oxus River]] thus became the boundary between the two rival empires.\n\n===Isma'il Muntasir's attempt to resurrect the Samanid state (1000\u20131005)===\n[[File:Isma'il Muntasir.jpg|thumb|270px|right|Artwork of [[Isma'il Muntasir]] in a battle.]]\n[[Isma'il Muntasir]] was the youngest son of Nuh II\u2014he was imprisoned by the Karakhanids after their conquest of Bukhara in 999. Some time later, Isma'il managed to escape to Khwarazm, where he gained support. Driving the Karakhanids out of Bukhara, he then moved on to and captured Samarkand. The approach of the Karakhanid army, however, forced Isma'il to give up all of his possessions, following which he travelled to Khorasan, where he captured Nishapur. Mahmud's army, however, made its way to the region, and Isma'il decided it necessary to flee again.\n\nIn 1003 Isma'il came back to Transoxiana, where he requested and received assistance from the Oghuz Turks of the [[Zarafshan]] valley. They defeated the Karakhanids in several battles, even when Nasr Khan was involved. For various reasons, however, Isma'il came to feel that he could not rely on the Oghuz to restore him, so he went back to Khorasan. He tried to gain Mahmud's support for a campaign to restore the Samanid state, but failed. Some time afterwards, he returned to the Zarafshan valley, where he gained the support of the Oghuz and others. A Karakhanid army was defeated in May 1004, but subsequently the Oghuz deserted Isma'il during another battle, and his army fell apart.\n\nFleeing to Khorasan yet again, Isma'il attempted to reenter Transoxiana in the end of 1004. The Karakhanids stopped this and Isma'il was nearly killed. Following this, he sought the hospitality of an [[Arab]] tribe near Merv. Their chief, however, killed Isma'il in 1005. His death marked the defeat of the last attempt to restore the Samanid state. Descendants of the Samanid family continued to live in Transoxiana where they were well regarded, but their power was relatively broken.\n\n===Iranian intermezzo===\nAlong with several other states, the Samanid Empire was part of the [[Iranian Intermezzo]], or \"Persian renaissance\". This period has been described as having a key importance in the formation of the Islamic civilization, both politically and culturally. In political terms, it saw an effective break up of the Abbasid power and the rise of several successor states such as the Samanids and Buyids while in cultural terms, it witnessed the rise of new Persian as an administrative and literary language.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=OeiKDwAAQBAJ&pg=PR19&dq=Medieval+Central+Asia+and+the+Persianate+World,+A.C.S.+Peacock,+D.G.+Tor,+Iranian+Intermezzo#v=onepage&q=Medieval%20Central%20Asia%20and%20the%20Persianate%20World,%20A.C.S.%20Peacock,%20D.G.%20Tor,%20Iranian%20Intermezzo&f=true|title=Medieval Central Asia and the Persianate World: Iranian Tradition and Islamic Civilisation|last=Peacock|first=A. C. S.|last2=Tor|first2=D. G.|date=2017-08-30|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|isbn=9780857727435|language=en|page=xix}}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\n\n===Government===\n\n====Structure====\n[[File:MansurISamanidCoinHistoryofIran.jpg|thumb|right|A Samanid coin minted in Bukhara bearing the name of [[Mansur I]] ]]\n\nThe system of the Samanid state was modelled after the Abbasid system,{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=143}} which in turn was modelled after the Sasanian system.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=146}}{{sfn|Shahbazi|2005}} The ruler of the state was the ''[[amir]]'', and the provinces were governed by appointed governors or local [[vassal]] rulers. The main responsibility of both governors and local rulers was to collect taxes and support the Samanid ruler with troops if needed. The most important province in the Samanid Empire was Khorasan, which was initially given to a relative of the Samanid ruler or a local Iranian prince (such as the [[Muhtajids]]), but was later given to one of his most trusted slaves. The governor of Khorasan was normally the ''[[sipah-salar]]'' (commander-in-chief).{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=143}}\n\nLike in the Abbasid Caliphate, Turkic slaves could rise to high office in the Samanid state, which would sometimes give them enough power to nearly make the ruler their puppet.{{sfn|Frye|1975|p=143}}\n\n====The nature of political authority under the Samanids====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n===Cultural and religious efforts===\n\n\nThe Samanids revived [[Persian culture]] by patronizing [[Rudaki]],<ref>\"Mihragan\", J. Calmard, ''The Encyclopedia of Islam'', Vol.VII, Ed. C. E.Bosworth, E. van Donzel, W. P. Heinrichs and C. Pellat, (Brill, 1993), 18.</ref> [[Bal'ami]] and [[Daqiqi]].<ref>C.E. Bosworth, ''The Ghaznavids: 994\u20131040'', (Edinburgh University Press, 1963), 131.</ref> The Samanids determinedly propagated [[Sunni Islam]], and repressed [[Ismaili]] [[Shiism]]<ref>An Ismaili Heresiography: The \"Bab Al-Shaytan\" from Abu Tammam's Kitab Al ... By Wilferd Madelung, Paul Ernest Walker, pg. 5</ref> but were more tolerant of [[Twelver]] Shiism.<ref name=\"Elton L. Daniel pg. 74\"/> Islamic architecture and Islamo-Persian culture was spread deep into the heart of Central Asia by the Samanids. Following the first complete translation of the [[Qur'an]] into Persian, during the 9th century, populations under the Samanid empire began accepting Islam in significant numbers.<ref>Michael Dillon, ''Xinjiang: China's Muslim far Northwest'', (RoutledgeCurzon, 2004), 11.</ref>\n\nThrough zealous missionary work as many as 30,000 tents of [[Turkic peoples|Turks]] came to profess Islam and later under the Ghaznavids more than 55,000 under the [[Hanafi]] school of thought. The mass conversion of the Turks to Islam eventually led to a growing influence of the [[Ghaznavids]], who would later rule the region.\n\nAgriculture and trading were the economic bases of the Samanid State. The Samanids were heavily involved in trading&nbsp;\u2013 even with Europe, as thousands of Samanid coins that have been found in the Baltic and Scandinavian countries testify.<ref>History of Bukhara, By Narshakhi trans. Richard N. Frye, pg. 143</ref>\n\nAnother lasting contribution of the Samanids to the history of Islamic art is the pottery known as Samanid Epigraphic Ware: plates, bowls, and pitchers fired in a white slip and decorated only with calligraphy, often elegantly and rhythmically written.  The Arabic phrases used in this calligraphy are generally more or less generic well wishes, or Islamic admonitions to good table manners.\n\n===Scholarship===\n\n====Avicenna and Abu Rayhan al-Biruni====\n\n===Literature===\n[[File:The Sasanian King Khusraw and Courtiers in a Garden, Page from a manuscript of the Shahnama (Book of Kings) of Firdawsi, late 15th-early 16th century.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanian]] king [[Khosrow II]] and his courtiers in a garden'', page from a manuscript of the [[Shahnameh]], late 15th-early 16th century. [[Brooklyn Museum]].]]\nIn the 9th and 10th centuries, there was a large amount of growth in literature, mostly in poetry. It was during the Samanid period that [[Persian literature]] appeared in Transoxiana and was formally recognized.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}} The advancement of an Islamic New Persian literature thus started in Transoxiana and Khorasan instead of [[Fars Province|Fars]], the homeland of the Persians. The best known poets of the Samanid period were [[Rudaki]] (d. 941), [[Daqiqi]] (d. 977) and [[Ferdowsi]] (d. 1020).{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}}\n\nAlthough Persian was the most-favored language, Arabic continued to enjoy a high status and was still popular among the members of the Samanid family.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}} For example, [[Al-Tha'\u0101lib\u012b|al-Tha'alibi]] wrote an Arabic anthology named Yatimat al-dahr (\"The Unique Pearl\"). The fourth section of the anthology included a detailed account of the poets that lived under the Samanids. It also states that the poets of Khwarazm mostly wrote in Arabic.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}}\n\nThe acknowledged founder of Persian classical poetry, and a man of great perception, was Rudaki, who was born in the village of [[Rudaki, Tajikistan|Panjrudak]], which is today part of the [[Panjakent District]] in [[Tajikistan]].{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=97}} Rudaki was already becoming popular during his early years, due to his poems, his voice, and his great skill in using the [[Chang (instrument)|chang]] (an Iranian instrument similar to the [[harp]]). He was shortly invited to the Samanid court, where he stayed almost the rest of his life. Fewer than 2,000 lines of his poetry have survived, but are enough to prove his great poetic skills\u2014he perfected every basic verse form of medieval Persian poetry: mathnawi, [[qasida]], [[ghazal]] and [[ruba'i]].{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}}\n\n<div style=\"text-align: center;\">\n\"Look at the cloud, how it cries like a grieving man\n: Thunder moans like a lover with a broken heart.\n: Now and then the sun peeks from behind the clouds\n: Like a prisoner hiding from the guard.\"&nbsp;\u2013 Rudaki\n</div>\n\nAnother prominent poet was [[Shahid Balkhi]], born in the village of Jakhudanak near Balkh. Not much is known about his life, but he is mentioned as being one of the best poets in the court of Nasr II, and one of the best scholars of the age. He was also a student of Rudaki, and had close relations with him. He died in 936, a few years before Rudaki's death. His death saddened Rudaki, who afterwards wrote an emotional [[elegy]] about him.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}}\n\nDaqiqi, who was a native of [[Tus, Iran|Tus]], began his career at the court of the [[Muhtajids|Muhtajid]] ruler [[Abu'l Muzaffar ibn Muhammad]] in [[Chaghaniyan]], and was later invited to the Samanid court.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}} Under the Samanids, a special interest arose in ancient Iranian legends and heroic traditions, thus inspiring Daqiqi to write the [[Shahnameh]] (\"The Book of Kings\"), a long [[epic poem]] based on the history of the Iranians. However, by his death in 977, he had only managed to complete a small part of it, which was about the conflict between [[Vishtaspa|Gushtasp]] and [[Arjasp]].{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}}\n\nHowever, the most prominent poet of that age was Ferdowsi, born in Tus in 940 to a ''dehqan'' family. It was during his youth that there was a period of growth under the Samanids. The rapid growth of interest in ancient Iranian history made him continue the work of Daqiqi, completing the Shahnameh in 994, only a few years before the fall of the Samanid Empire. He later completed a second version of the Shahnameh in 1010, which he presented to the Ghaznavid Sultan Mahmud. However, his work was not as appreciated by the Ghaznavids as it had been by the Samanids.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=98}}\n\n===Music===\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n===Population===\nUnder the Samanid Empire, the [[Zarafshan]] valley, [[Qashqadaryo Region|Kashka Darya]] and [[Usrushana]] were populated by [[Sogdia]]ns; [[Tukharistan]] by the Bactrians; [[Khwarezm]] by the Khwarazmians; the [[Fergana Valley|Ferghana valley]] by the Ferghanans; southern [[Greater Khorasan|Khorasan]] by Khorasanians; and the [[Pamir mountains]] and environs by the [[Saka]] and other early Iranian peoples. All these groups were of Iranian ethnicity and spoke dialects of [[Middle Iranian]] and [[New Persian]]. In the words of Negmatov, \"they were the basis for the emergence and gradual consolidation of what became an Eastern Persian-Tajik ethnic identity.\"{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=101}}\n\n===Language===\nFerghana, Samarkand, and Bukhara were starting to be linguistically [[Persian language|Persianized]] in originally Khwarazmian and Sogdian areas during Samanid rule.<ref name=\"NourzhanovBleuer2013\">{{cite book|author1=Kirill Nourzhanov|author2=Christian Bleuer|title=Tajikistan: A Political and Social History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nR6oAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA30#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=8 October 2013|publisher=ANU E Press|isbn=978-1-925021-16-5|pages=30\u2013}}</ref> The Persian language spread and led to the extinction of Eastern Iranian languages like [[Bactrian language|Bactrian]] and [[Khwarezmian language|Khwarezmian]] with only a tiny amount of [[Sogdian language|Sogdian]]-descended [[Yaghnobi language|Yaghnobi]] speakers remaining among the now Persian-speaking Tajik population of Central Asia.  This was due to the fact that the Arab-Islamic army which invaded Central Asia also included some Persians who later governed the region like the Samanids.<ref name=\"Bergne2007\">{{cite book|author=Paul Bergne|title=The Birth of Tajikistan: National Identity and the Origins of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3coojMwTKU8C&pg=PA5#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 June 2007|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-283-7|pages=5\u2013}}</ref> Persian was rooted into Central Asia by the Samanids.<ref name=\"Paul Bergne 6\">{{cite book|author=Paul Bergne|title=The Birth of Tajikistan: National Identity and the Origins of the Republic|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3coojMwTKU8C&pg=PA6#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=15 June 2007|publisher=I.B.Tauris|isbn=978-1-84511-283-7|pages=6\u2013}}</ref>\n\n===Intellectual life===\nIn the 9th and 10th centuries, intellectual life in Transoxiana and Khorasan reached a high level. In the words of N.N. Negmatov, \"It was inevitable that the local Samanid dynasty, seeking support among its literate classes, should cultivate and promote local cultural traditions, literacy and literature.\"{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=93}}\n\nThe main Samanid towns&nbsp;\u2013 [[Bukhara]], [[Samarkand]], [[Balkh]], [[Merv]], [[Nishapur]], [[Khujand]], [[Bunjikath]], [[Hulbuk]], [[Termez]] and others, became the major cultural centres under the state. Scholars, poets, artists and other men of education from many Muslim countries assembled in the Samanid capital of Bukhara, where a rich soil was created for the prosper of creative thought, thus making it one of the most distinguished cultural centres of the Eastern world. An outstanding library known as ''Siw\u0101n al-hikma'' (\"Storehouse of Wisdom\") was put together in Bukhara, known for its various types of books.{{sfn|Litvinsky|1998|p=94}}\n\n=== Arts ===\n[[File:Two Bowls with Figures and a Footed Plate with Birds MET DP258911.jpg|thumb|Example of figural earthenware ceramics from Samanid period.]]\n\n==== Crafts ====\n[[File:Bowl with Arabic Inscription.jpg|thumb|Bowl with Arabic Inscription]]\nDue to extensive excavations at [[Nishapur]], Iran, in the mid-twentieth century, Samanid pottery is well-represented in Islamic art collections around the world. These ceramics are largely made from [[earthenware]] and feature either calligraphic inscriptions of Arabic proverbs, or colorful figural decorations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grube|first=Ernst J.|date=February 1965|title=The Art of Islamic Pottery|journal=The Metropolitan Museum of Art Bulletin|volume=23|issue=6|pages=209\u2013228|doi=10.2307/3258167|issn=0026-1521|jstor=3258167}}</ref> The Arabic proverbs often speak to the values of \"Adab\" culture\u2014hospitality, generosity, and modesty.<ref>Pancaroglu, Oya. \"Serving wisdom: The contents of Samanid epigraphic pottery.\" Studies in Islamic and Later Indian Art from the Arthur M. Sackler Museum, Harvard University Art Museum (2002): 58-68.</ref>\n\nThe bowl with the Arabic inscription shown here is from Iran, during the Samanid period in the 10th century. It has a white slip with black slip decoration under a transparent glaze. There is calligraphic decoration all around the bowl. It is elongated at some points and compressed in other areas of the letter to the point where it almost looks abstract. Right in the center of the bowl is a black dot. If the bowl is looked at closely there are cracks and marks that have occurred over time. What would once have been a white bowl is now stained yellow in some areas. The calligraphy looks well thought out and planned. Each letter is well spaced, and the whole saying fits perfectly around the bowl. This may be because the artists used to practice beforehand on paper. The saying translates to \u201cPlanning before work protects you from regret; prosperity and peace\u201d\n\n===Economy===\n\n====Agriculture====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n====Mining====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}<br />\n\n====Material culture====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n====Domestic and external trade====\n\n{{Empty section|date=January 2016}}\n\n==Legacy==\n\nIn commending the Samanids, the epic Persian poet [[Ferdowsi]] says of them:\n\n<blockquote>\n\u06a9\u062c\u0627 \u0622\u0646 \u0628\u0632\u0631\u06af\u0627\u0646 \u0633\u0627\u0633\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646<br/>\n\u0632 \u0628\u0647\u0631\u0627\u0645\u06cc\u0627\u0646 \u062a\u0627 \u0628\u0647 \u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646\u06cc\u0627\u0646\n</blockquote>\n\n\"Where have all the great [[Sasanian Empire|Sasanians]] gone?<br/>\nFrom the [[Bahram V of Persia|Bahr\u0101mids]] to the Samanids what has come upon?\"\n\nA Bukharian historian writing in 943 stated that [[Ismail Samani]]: <blockquote>\"was indeed worthy and right for [[padishah]]ship. He was an intelligent, just, compassionate person, one possessing reason and prescience...he conducted affairs with justice and good ethics.  Whoever tyrannized people he would punish...In affairs of state he was always impartial.\"<ref>Edward Allworth, ''The Modern Uzbeks: from the fourteenth century to the present : a cultural history'', p. 19</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe celebrated scholar [[Nizam al-Mulk]], in his famous work ''[[Siyasatnama]]'', stated that Ismail Samani: <blockquote>\"was extremely just, and his good qualities were many.  He had pure faith in God (to Him be power and glory) and he was generous to the poor&nbsp;\u2013 to name only one of his notable virtues.<ref>''The book of government, or, Rules for kings: the Siyar al-Muluk'', or, ''Siyasat-nama of Nizam al-Mulk'', tr. Hubert Darke, p. 14</ref></blockquote>\n\nThe [[Somoni]] currency of [[Tajikistan]] is named after the Samanids.  A notable airline based in [[Dushanbe]] is also named [[Somon Air]]. Also, the highest mountain in Tajikistan and in the former [[Soviet Union]] is named after Ismail Samani.<ref>[[Richard Foltz]], ''A History of the Tajiks: Iranians of the East'', London: Bloomsbury, 2019, p. 68.</ref> The mountain was formerly known as \"Stalin Peak\" and \"Communism Peak\" but in 1998 the name was officially changed to [[Ismoil Somoni Peak]].\n\n==Samanid rulers==\n{|style=\"width:100%;\" class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:17%;\"| Bukhara\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:17%;\"| Samarkand\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:17%;\"| Ferghana\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:15%;\"| Shash\n! style=\"background:#f0dc82; width:15%;\"| Herat\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Saman Khuda]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646 \u062e\u062f\u0627}}<br/> <small>(A Persian landowner from the village of Saman in [[Balkh]] province in northern [[Afghanistan]], he arrived in [[Merv]] to the court of the [[Umayyad]] governor of Khorasan, [[Asad ibn Abdallah al-Qasri]], under whose influence he became a Muslim and served the governor till his death. He was the founder of the Samanid dynasty)</small>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Asad ibn Saman]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u0633\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0633\u0627\u0645\u0627\u0646}}<br/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Nuh ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0646\u0648\u062d \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013841/2\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ahmad ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013864/5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Yahya ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u06cc\u062d\u06cc\u06cc\u0670 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013855\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ilyas ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0633 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013856\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Ahmad ibn Asad]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0633\u062f}}<br/>819\u2013864/5\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ibrahim ibn Ilyas]]<br/> {{lang-fa| \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u06cc\u0627\u0633}}<br/>856\u2013867\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Isma'il ibn Ahmad|Abu Ibrahim Isma'il ibn Ahmad]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0627\u0628\u0648 \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u0627\u0633\u0645\u0627\u0639\u06cc\u0644 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>892\u2013907\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Nasr I]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u0646\u0635\u0631 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>864\u2013892\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Ya'qub ibn Ahmad]]<br/> {{lang-fa|\u06cc\u0639\u0642\u0648\u0628 \u0628\u0646 \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f}}<br/>?\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Saffarids]]<br/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Isma'il ibn Ahmad|Abu Ibrahim Isma'il ibn 