son-classes-due-to-coronavirus/|title=Universities cancelling in-person classes due to coronavirus|website=SowetanLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.up.ac.za/news/post_2881150-update-postponement-of-contact-classes-and-rescheduling-of-academic-calendar- |title = UPDATE: Postponement of contact classes and rescheduling of academic calendar}}</ref>\n*[[List of comic book conventions|Comic Con]] Cape Town, postponed to 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/entertainment/whats-on/cape-town/comic-con-cape-town-postponed-to-2021-45138721|title=Comic Con Cape Town postponed to 2021|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*Agricultural events such as the [[Pietermaritzburg]] Royal Show, SA Cheese Festival, Qualit\u00e9 Awards Dinner, and Agri-Expo Western Cape Youth Show, cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foodformzansi.co.za/covid-19-farmers-urged-to-protect-themselves-workers/|title=COVID-19: Farmers urged to protect themselves, workers|last=Ngcakani|first=Noluthando|date=2020-03-16|website=Food For Mzansi|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Wimpy (restaurant)|Wimpy]] [[Lifesaving South Africa]], national championships cancelled.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iol.co.za/sport/wimpy-lifesaving-south-africa-national-championships-cancelled-44956403|title=Wimpy Lifesaving South Africa National Championships cancelled|website=www.iol.co.za|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*[[Scouts South Africa]], all Scouting activity suspended until schools reopen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scouts.org.za/2020/03/16/scouting-suspended-in-response-to-covid-19/|title=Scouting suspended in response to COVID-19|website=www.scouts.org.za|date=16 March 2020|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[Johannesburg|City of Johannesburg]], all public facilities closed indefinitely including public swimming pools, recreational and civic centres, stadiums, libraries, sporting facilities, and the [[Johannesburg Zoo]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://citizen.co.za/news/south-africa/government/2257497/city-of-joburg-closes-all-public-facilities-including-pools-theatres-and-the-zoo/|title=City of Joburg closes all public facilities, including pools, theatres and the zoo |agency=News24 Wire |website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n*The [[EThekwini Metropolitan Municipality|Ethekhwini Metropolitan Municipality]] closed all of [[Durban]]'s public facilities including swimming pools, beaches, libraries, community halls, and museums while restrictions have been put in place for the [[Durban Art Gallery]] and cemeteries to only allow 50 people at a time.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/lifestyle/383319/durban-bans-swimming-at-the-beach/|title=Durban bans swimming at the beach|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n===Economic impact===\n[[File:Philippi 20200407 112336.jpg|thumb|Volunteers in [[Philippi, Cape Town]] packing [[CARE Package|food parcels]] to be given out to the needy during the COVID 19 pandemic lockdown. The lockdown had a seriously negative impact on South Africa's economy that hit the poor and unemployed especially hard.]]{{See also|Socio-economic impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nAt the beginning of the national shutdown on 27 March South African economists predicted that the pandemic could cause a 2.5% to 10% contraction of [[Economy of South Africa|South Africa's total GDP]] in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/economy/sa-economy-could-crater-up-to-10-this-year/|title=SA economy could crater up to 10% this year|date=2020-03-25|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> The national lockdown and resulting economic slowdown reduced demand for electricity by more than {{val|7500}} MW thereby temporarily reducing the impact of the long running [[South African energy crisis]].<ref>{{Cite web\n|url=https://www.iol.co.za/news/south-africa/gauteng/eskom-will-keep-the-lights-on-during-21-day-lockdown-45708578\n|title=Eskom will keep the lights on during 21-day lockdown\n|date=2020-03-28\n|publisher=Independent Media\n|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n====Stock market news====\nThe [[JSE Limited|JSE]] lost 15% of its value in the week ending 13 March 2020, its worst week in 21 years.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businesslive.co.za/bd/markets/2020-03-13-market-wrap-jse-has-worst-week-since-1998-as-pandemic-plagues-investors/\n|title=MARKET WRAP: JSE has worst week since 1998 as pandemic plagues investors\n|date=2020-03-13\n|first1=Odwa\n|last1=Mjo\n|work=BusinessLIVE\n|access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, the [[South African Reserve Bank]] governor, [[Lesetja Kganyago]] announced a reduction of the country's [[Repurchase agreement|repo rate]] by 100 basis points or 1 percentage point to 5.25%.<ref name=\"RepoSlashed\">{{cite web|url=https://www.moneyweb.co.za/news/south-africa/live-repo-rate-decision/|title=Repo rate slashed by 1%|last=Mar 2020|first=Suren Naidoo / 19|date=2020-03-19|website=Moneyweb|access-date=2020-03-20}}</ref>\n\n====Banking and retail====\nRetailers like Clicks, [[Pick n Pay Stores|Pick n Pay]], and [[Woolworths Holdings Limited|Woolworths]] have some limitations on the number of the same items customers may buy.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/cornonavirus-linked-panic-buying-retailers-ration-stock-2020-3\n|title=Woolworths stops food demonstrations, limits items per customer \u2013 here's what other retailers are doing\n|date=2020-03-19\n|first1=Jay\n|last1=Caboz\n|publisher=Business Insider\n|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 19 March, [[Minister of Trade and Industry (South Africa)|Minister of Trade and Industry]] [[Ebrahim Patel]] signed a government gazette that enforces [[price controls]] on essential items and that could see [[Price gouging|price gougers]] punished with measures including a R10 million fine, a fine equivalent to 10% of a firm's turnover, or [[Imprisonment|12 months in prison]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://businesstech.co.za/news/business/383217/new-regulations-bring-coronavirus-price-controls-for-certain-high-demand-products-heres-what-is-on-the-list/|title=New regulations bring coronavirus price controls for certain high-demand products \u2013 here's what is on the list|last=Writer|first=Staff|website=businesstech.co.za|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> On 22 March, [[Standard Bank]] announced a 90-day [[Forbearance|payment holiday]] for small and medium-sized business and students to try and shield them from the economic impact of the outbreak, starting from 1 April.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businessinsider.co.za/coronavirus-standard-bank-gives-businesses-a-debt-holiday-2020-3|title=Coronavirus: Standard Bank gives businesses, students a debt holiday|website=BusinessInsider|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Misinformation ==\n{{Main|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nThe spreading of [[fake news]] and other misinformation in South Africa about the virus is an offence punishable with either a fine, six months' imprisonment, or both.<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" />\n\nThe arrival of the COVID-19 virus in South Africa saw an increase in the dissemination of misinformation about the virus on social media and other platforms. These range from messages minimising the virus's harm in the country<ref name=\"MaverickFake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailymaverick.co.za/article/2020-03-31-viral-outbreak-fake-news-spreads-in-sa-in-tandem-with-covid-19/|title=Coronavirus Fact Check#1: Viral outbreak: Fake news spreads in SA in tandem with Covid-19|last=Davis|first=Rebecca|website=Daily Maverick|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> to the propagation of [[Conspiracy theory|conspiracy theories]] about government actions to control the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/fake-news-no-covid-19-testing-kits-are-not-contaminated-20200406|title=FAKE NEWS: No, Covid-19 testing kits are not contaminated|last=|first=|date=2020-04-06|website=News24|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nOne individual was arrested for posting a video showing himself drinking in public with friends following the national lockdown whilst stating that there was \"nothing called corona here\".<ref name=\"MaverickFake\" /> In another incident a man claimed that 10,000 government officials would be going door-to-door using contaminated test kits to test people for the virus.<ref name=\"News24Fake\" /> A conspiracy theory that [[Bill Gates]] wished to test a COVID-19 \"vaccine\" in Africa or South Africa first caused significant controversy on social media<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/news/south-africa/2020-04-06-bill-gates-trevor-noah-death-threats--that-vaccine-how-it-all-went-wrong/|title=Bill Gates, Trevor Noah, death threats & that vaccine: how it all went wrong|website=TimesLIVE|language=en-ZA|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> following the publication of a now retracted story in [[News24]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news24.com/SouthAfrica/News/apology-to-the-bill-and-melinda-gates-foundation-for-africa-vaccine-story-20200405|title=Apology to the Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation for 'Africa vaccine' story|date=2020-04-05|website=News24|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref> [[Trevor Noah]] stated that he received hate mail for conducting the interview on ''[[The Daily Show]]'' with Gates where it was falsely reported that Gates made the claim.<ref name=\"Trevor Noah\" />\n\nFake news that [[5G|5G cellular]] technology was the true cause of COVID-19 symptoms also spread in the country during this period as it also did in other countries around the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://citizen.co.za/lifestyle/technology/2263396/zweli-mkhize-says-5g-causing-covid-19-deaths-is-just-fake-news/|title=Zweli Mkhize says '5G causing Covid-19 deaths' is just fake news|last=Cilliers|first=Charles|website=The Citizen|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|South Africa|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nicd.ac.za/ National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)]\n*[https://sacoronavirus.co.za/ Government COVID-19 website]\n*[https://www.gov.za/taxonomy/term/707 Government officials' speeches]\n*[https://datastudio.google.com/u/0/reporting/1b60bdc7-bec7-44c9-ba29-be0e043d8534/page/hrUIB Dashboard by Data Science for Social Impact Research Group, University of Pretoria]\n*[https://coronamap.co.za Corona virus map]\n*[https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019 World Health Organization (WHO) COVID-19 pandemic information]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Africa| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jeandr\u00e9 du Toit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:04-14 cases, deaths, tests", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_South_Africa"}
{"title_page": "Windows Server 2008 R2", "text_new": "{{short description|server operating system by Microsoft released in 2009}}\n{{Infobox OS\n| name = Windows Server 2008 R2\n| version of = [[Windows NT]]\n| logo = [[File:Windows logo - 2006.svg|64px]]\n| screenshot = Windows_Server_2008_R2_Datacenter.png\n| caption = Screenshot of Windows Server 2008 R2 showing the Server Manager application which is automatically opened when an administrator logs on.\n| developer = Microsoft\n| family = [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| working state = Current<!-- \"Current\", \"Discontinued\" (operating systems), or \"No longer supported\" (releases) -->\n| source model = {{ubl\n  | [[Proprietary software|Closed-source]]\n  | [[Source-available software|Source-available]] (through [[Shared Source Initiative]])\n}}\n| first release date = {{Start date and age|2009|7|22}}\n| first release url = http://blogs.technet.com/windowsserver/archive/2009/07/22/windows-server-2008-r2-rtm.aspx\n| GA date = {{Start date and age|2009|10|22}}\n| GA url = http://www.microsoft.com/presspass/features/2009/Jun09/06-02SteveGuggenheimer.mspx\n| release version = Service Pack 1 with Platform Update or later update rollup (build 6.1.7601)\n| release date = {{Start date and age|2013|8|27}}\n| release url = http://blogs.technet.com/windowsserver/archive/2009/07/22/windows-server-2008-r2-rtm.aspx\n| preview version = \n| preview date = \n| preview url = \n| marketing target = Business\n| programmed in = \n| language = <!-- Supported human languages (English, French, Italian, Arabic, ...) -->\n| language count = \n| language footnote = \n| update model = [[Windows Update]], [[Windows Server Update Services]], [[System Center Configuration Manager|SCCM]]\n| package manager = <!-- dpkg, rpm, Windows installer, etc. -->\n| supported platforms = [[x86-64]], [[Itanium]]\n| kernel type = [[Hybrid kernel|Hybrid]] ([[Windows NT kernel]])\n| ui = [[Windows shell]] ([[Graphical user interface|Graphical]])\n| license = [[Commercial software]] ([[Retail]], [[volume licensing]], [[Microsoft Software Assurance]])\n| preceded by = [[Windows Server 2008]] (2008)\n| succeeded by = [[Windows Server 2012]] (2012)\n| website = {{URL|https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/windowsserver/bb310558}}\n| support status = Mainstream support ended on January 13, 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://support.microsoft.com/lifecycle/search/default.aspx?sort=PN&alpha=Windows+Server+2008+R2&Filter=FilterNO | title=Windows Server 2008 R2 Lifecycle Policy | author=Microsoft | publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref><br/>Extended support ended January 14, 2020.<br />\nExtended Security Updates paid in yearly installments for 1, 2, or 3 years (or free for Windows Virtual Desktop users) until at most January 10, 2023 only for Standard, Enterprise and Datacenter volume licensed editions.<ref>https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/help/4497181/lifecycle-faq-extended-security-updates</ref><!--July 12, 2022 for Windows Embedded Standard 7 and October 14, 2024 for Windows Embedded POSReady 7--><ref>https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/cloud-platform/extended-security-updates</ref><ref>https://www.crn.com.au/news/microsoft-starts-selling-extended-support-for-windows-server-2008-520013</ref><br/><br/>Installing Service Pack 1 is required for users to receive updates and support after April 9, 2013.<ref name=sup1>{{cite web |url=http://support.microsoft.com/lifecycle/?c2=14019 |title=Microsoft Support Lifecycle | website=Support | publisher=Microsoft | accessdate=February 20, 2012}}</ref><ref name=sup2>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.windows.com/windows/b/springboard/archive/2013/02/14/windows-7-rtm-end-of-support-is-right-around-the-corner.aspx |title=Windows 7 RTM End Of Support Is Right Around The Corner |work=Springboard Series Blog |publisher=Microsoft |date=February 14, 2013 |accessdate=March 27, 2013 |first=Stephen L |last=Rose |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502231039/http://blogs.windows.com/windows/b/springboard/archive/2013/02/14/windows-7-rtm-end-of-support-is-right-around-the-corner.aspx |archive-date=May 4, 2017 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| other articles = * [[Windows Server 2008]]\n* [[Development of Windows 7]]\n* [[Features new to Windows 7]]\n* [[Features removed from Windows 7]]\n| date = January 2009 <!-- approximate date of template insertion for dating hidden maintenance categories -->\n}}\n'''Windows Server 2008 R2''' is<!--Do NOT change to \"was\". This violates [[MOS:TENSE]], which specifies that all articles on operating systems are written in previous tense, even if discontinued.--> a [[Server (computing)|server]] [[operating system]] produced by [[Microsoft]]. It was released to [[released to manufacturing|OEM hardware partners]] on July 22, 2009<ref>{{cite web|author=Server and Cloud Platform Team |url=http://blogs.technet.com/windowsserver/archive/2009/07/22/windows-server-2008-r2-rtm.aspx |title=Windows Server 2008 R2 Reaches the RTM Milestone! |publisher=Blogs.technet.com |date=2009-07-22 |accessdate=2011-06-15}}</ref> and became [[General availability|generally available]] on October 22, that year.<ref name=\"bott20090511\">{{cite web|url=http://news.microsoft.com/2009/06/02/windows-7-and-windows-server-2008-r2-timelines-shared-at-computex/|title=Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 Timelines Shared at Computex|last=|first=|date=June 3, 2009|website=News Center|publisher=Microsoft|location=Taipei, Taiwan}}</ref> It is the successor to the [[Windows Vista]]-based [[Windows Server 2008]], released the previous year.\n\nEnhancements in Windows Server 2008 R2 include new functionality for [[Active Directory]], new [[Hardware virtualization|virtualization]] and management features, version 7.5 of the [[Internet Information Services]] [[web server]] and support for up to 256<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com/windowsserver2008/en/us/2008-dc.aspx |title=Windows Server 2008 R2 Datacenter Edition Overview |publisher=Microsoft.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-15}}</ref> logical processors. It is built on the same [[Kernel (computing)|kernel]] used with the client-oriented [[Windows 7]], and is the first server operating system released by Microsoft to exclusively support 64-bit processors.\n\nMicrosoft stopped providing security updates and technical support for Windows Server 2008 R2 RTM since April 9, 2013, and Service Pack 1 must be installed to continue receiving support and updates on any given Windows operating system. Seven editions of Windows Server 2008 R2 were released: Foundation, Standard, Enterprise, Datacenter, Web, [[Windows HPC Server 2008|HPC Server]] and [[Itanium]], as well as Windows Storage Server 2008 R2. A [[home server]] variant called [[Windows Home Server 2011]] was also released. \n\nWindows Server 2008 R2 was succeeded by [[Windows 8]]-based [[Windows Server 2012]].\n\n==History==\nMicrosoft introduced Windows Server 2008 R2 at the 2008 [[Professional Developers Conference]] as the server variant of [[Windows 7]].\n\nOn January 7, 2009, a [[beta release]] of Windows Server 2008 R2 was made available to subscribers of Microsoft's [[Microsoft TechNet|TechNet]] and [[Microsoft Developer Network|MSDN]] programs, as well as those participating in the Microsoft Connect program for Windows 7. Two days later, the beta was released to the public via the Microsoft Download Center.<ref name=\"2008r2publicbeta\">{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/microsoft/news/2009/01/windows-7-public-beta-is-available-now.ars |title=Windows 7 public beta is available now|author=Emil Protalinski}}</ref>\n\nOn April 30, 2009, the [[release candidate]] was made available to subscribers of TechNet and MSDN.<ref name=\"2008r2rc\">{{cite web\n|url = http://edge.technet.com/Media/Announcing-Windows-Server-2008-R2-Release-Candidate-RC/ |title = Announcing Windows Server 2008 R2 Release Candidate (RC)|publisher = Microsoft TechNet}}</ref> On May 5, 2009, the release candidate was made available to the general public via the Microsoft download center.<ref name=\"Server2008R2RCpublic\">{{cite web |url = http://www.microsoft.com/downloads/details.aspx?FamilyId=a4e21e2e-e992-4aec-9ed4-086de21632a2 |title = Download Windows Server 2008 R2 RC .iso images (May2009)|publisher = Microsoft}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''Windows Server Blog'',<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://blogs.technet.com/windowsserver/archive/2009/07/22/when-to-expect-windows-server-2008-r2-rtm.aspx|title=When to expect Windows Server 2008 R2 RTM|last=House|first=Crissy|date=22 July 2009|website=Windows Server Blog|publisher=[[Microsoft]]|access-date=}}</ref> the following are the dates of the year 2009 when Microsoft Windows Server 2008 R2 has been made available to various distribution channels:\n\n* [[OEM]]s received Windows Server 2008 R2 in English and all language packs on July 29. The remaining languages were available around August 11.\n* [[Independent software vendor]] (ISV) and [[independent hardware vendor]] (IHV) partners have been able to download Windows Server 2008 R2 from MSDN starting on August 14.\n* IT professionals with TechNet subscriptions were able to download Windows Server 2008 R2 and obtain product keys for English, French, German, Italian, and Spanish variants beginning August 14 and all remaining languages beginning August 21.\n* Developers with MSDN subscriptions have been able to download and obtain product keys for Windows Server 2008 R2 in English, French, German, Italian, and Spanish starting August 14 and all remaining languages starting August 21.\n* Microsoft Partner Program (MPP) gold/certified members were able to download Windows Server 2008 R2 through the MPP portal on August 19.\n* [[Volume licensing]] customers with an existing Software Assurance (SA) contracts were able to download Windows Server 2008 R2 on August 19 via the Volume License Service Center.\n* Volume licensing customers without an SA were able to purchase Windows Server 2008 R2 through volume licensing by September 1.\n\nAdditionally, qualifying students have been able to download Windows Server 2008 R2 Standard edition in 15 languages from the [[Microsoft Imagine]]  program (known as DreamSpark at the time).<ref name=\"R2OnDreamSpark\">{{cite web |url = https://www.dreamspark.com/Products/Product.aspx?ProductId=17 |title = Windows Server 2008 R2 on DreamSpark |publisher = Microsoft}}</ref>\n\nMicrosoft has announced that Server 2008 R2 will be the last version of [[Windows]] supporting the [[Itanium]] architecture, with its extended support ending earlier than for the regular non-Itanium edition or \"<!--Mainstream support for Windows Server 2008 for Itanium-Based Systems (and R2) will end [already has] [..] while extended support will continue -->until July 10, 2018.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://blogs.technet.microsoft.com/windowsserver/2010/04/02/windows-server-2008-r2-to-phase-out-itanium/ |title=Windows Server 2008 R2 to Phase Out Itanium |quote=Why the change?  The natural evolution of the x86 64-bit (\u201cx64\u201d) architecture has led to the creation of processors and servers which deliver the scalability and reliability needed for today\u2019s \u201cmission-critical\u201d workloads. |work=Windows Server Blog}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.computerworld.com/article/2516742/computer-hardware/microsoft-ending-support-for-itanium.html |title=Microsoft ending support for Itanium |quote=SQL Server 2008 R2 and Visual Studio 2010 are also the last versions to support Itanium.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rcpmag.com/articles/2010/04/05/microsoft-dropping-itanium-support.aspx|title=Microsoft Dropping Itanium Support \u2013 Redmond Channel Partner|website=Redmond Channel Partner|language=en|access-date=2018-05-14}}</ref>\n\n==New features==\n{{See also|Features new to Windows 7}}\nA reviewer guide published by the company describes several areas of improvement in R2.<ref name=\"2008r2guide\">{{cite web\n|url=http://download.microsoft.com/download/6/E/3/6E3E4529-27E3-48EC-B7E7-1A93242D3AE1/Windows_Server_2008_R2_Reviewers_Guide_(BETA).doc\n|title=Windows Server 2008 R2 Reviewers Guide\n|date=November 2008\n|accessdate=2009-08-31\n|publisher=Microsoft\n}}</ref> These include new virtualization capabilities ([[Live Migration]], [[Cluster Shared Volumes]] using [[High-availability cluster|Failover Clustering]] and [[Hyper-V]]), reduced power consumption, a new set of management tools and new [[Active Directory]] capabilities such as a \"recycle bin\" for deleted objects. IIS 7.5 has been added to this release which also includes updated [[FTP]] server services. Security enhancements include encrypted clientless authenticated VPN services through [[DirectAccess]] for clients using Windows 7, and the addition of [[DNSSEC]] support for [[Microsoft DNS|DNS Server Service]]. Even though DNSSEC as such is supported, only one signature algorithm is available:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/ee649277(WS.10).aspx |title=Understanding DNSSEC in Windows |publisher=Technet.microsoft.com |date=2009-10-07 |accessdate=2011-06-15}}</ref> #5 / RSA/SHA-1. Since many zones use a different algorithm \u2013 including the [[DNS root zone|root zone]] \u2013 this means that in reality Windows still can't serve as a recursive resolver.\n\nThe [[DHCP]] server supports a large number of enhancements<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.technet.com/teamdhcp/archive/2009/02/26/new-features-in-dhcp-for-windows-server-2008-r2-windows-7.aspx |title=New features in DHCP for Windows Server 2008 R2 / Windows 7 |publisher=Blogs.technet.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-15}}</ref> such as [[MAC address]]-based control filtering, converting active leases into reservations or [[Link Layer]] based filters, DHCppP ''Name protection'' for non-Windows machines to prevent name squatting, better performance through aggressive lease database caching, DHCP activity logging, auto-population of certain network interface fields, a wizard for split-scope configuration, ''DHCP Server role'' migration using WSMT, support for DHCPv6 Option 15 (User Class) and Option 32 (Information Refresh Time). The DHCP server runs in the context of the ''Network Service'' account which has fewer privileges to reduce potential damage if compromised.\n\nWindows Server 2008 R2 supports up to 64 physical processors<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com/windowsserver2008/en/us/scalability-ent.aspx |title=Windows Server 2008 R2: Scalability for the Enterprise Customer |publisher=Microsoft.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-15}}</ref> or up to 256 logical processors per system. (Only the Datacenter and Itanium editions can take advantage of the capability of 64 physical processors. Enterprise, the next-highest edition after those two, can only use 8.)<ref name=\"2008nov-morethan64processors\">{{cite web |url=http://www.microsoft.com/whdc/system/Sysinternals/MoreThan64proc.mspx|title=Windows7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 support more than 64 Processors in one System|date=November 2008|accessdate=2009-03-06|publisher=Microsoft}}</ref> When deployed in a file server role, new File Classification Infrastructure services allow files to be stored on designated servers in the enterprise based on business naming conventions, relevance to business processes and overall corporate policies.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://blogs.technet.com/windowsserver/archive/2009/04/30/r2-how-would-you-manage-without-it.aspx\n|title = R2: How Would You Manage Without It?\n|publisher = MSDN Blogs\n|accessdate = 2009-04-30\n}}</ref>\n\n[[Server Core]] includes a subset of the [[.NET Framework]], so that some applications (including [[ASP.NET]] web sites and [[Windows PowerShell]] 2.0) can be used.\n\nPerformance improvement was a major area of focus for this release; Microsoft has stated that work was done to decrease boot time, improve the efficiency of I/O operations while using less processing power, and generally improve the speed of storage devices, especially [[iSCSI]].\n\nActive Directory has several new features when raising the forest and domain functional levels<ref>{{cite web\n|url = https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/library/cc771132(WS.10).aspx\n|title = Appendix of Functional Level Features\n|publisher = Microsoft Technet\n|accessdate = 2009-10-06\n}}</ref> to Windows Server 2008 R2: Two added features are Authentication Mechanism Assurance and Automatic SPN Management. When raising the forest functional level, the Active Directory recycle bin feature is available and can be enabled using the Active Directory Module for PowerShell.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://praetorianprefect.com/archives/2009/10/server-2008-r2-active-directory-functional-levels/\n|title = Server 2008 R2: Active Directory Functional Levels\n|publisher = Praetorian Prefect\n|accessdate = 2009-10-06\n}}</ref>\n\n==Service Pack==\nOn February 9, 2011, Microsoft officially released Service Pack 1 (SP1) for Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 to OEM partners. Apart from bug fixes, it introduces two new major functions, RemoteFX and Dynamic Memory. RemoteFX enables the use of graphics hardware support for 3D graphics in a Hyper-V based VM.  Dynamic Memory makes it possible for a VM to only allocate as much physical RAM as is needed temporarily for its execution. On February 16, SP1 became available for MSDN and TechNet subscribers as well as volume licensing customers. As of February 22, SP1 is generally available for download via the Microsoft Download Center and available on Windows Update.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://windowsteamblog.com/windows/b/bloggingwindows/archive/2011/02/09/announcing-availability-of-windows-7-and-windows-server-2008-r2-sp1.aspx|title=Announcing Availability of Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 SP1}}</ref>\n\n==System requirements==\nSystem requirements for Windows Server 2008 R2 are as follows:<ref name=\"2008r2requirements\">{{cite web|url=http://www.microsoft.com/windowsserver2008/en/us/system-requirements.aspx |title=Windows Server 2008 R2: System Requirements |publisher=Microsoft.com |date= |accessdate=2011-06-15}}</ref>\n\n;Processor\n:1.4&nbsp;GHz [[x86-64]] or [[Itanium|Itanium 2]] processor\n;Memory\n:Minimum: 512&nbsp;[[Megabyte|MB]] [[Random access memory|RAM]] (may limit performance and some features)\n:Recommended: 2&nbsp;[[Gigabyte|GB]] [[Random access memory|RAM]]\n:Maximum: 8&nbsp;GB RAM (Foundation), 32&nbsp;GB RAM (Standard), or 2&nbsp;[[Terabyte|TB]] RAM (Enterprise, Datacenter and Itanium)\n;Display\n:[[Super VGA]] (800\u00d7600) or higher\n;Disk Space Requirements\n:Minimum (editions higher than Foundation): 32&nbsp;[[gigabyte|GB]] or more\n:Minimum (Foundation edition) 10&nbsp;[[gigabyte|GB]] or more.\n:Computers with more than 16&nbsp;GB of RAM require more disk space for paging and dump files.<ref name=\"2008r2requirements\" />\n;Other\n:DVD drive, keyboard and mouse, Internet access (required for [[Windows update|updates]] and online [[Windows Activation|activation]])\n\n==Editions==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size: 90%; width:100%; text-align: center\"\n|+Windows Server 2008 R2 edition comparison chart<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.microsoft.com/windowsserver2008/en/us/r2-compare-specs.aspx | title = Windows Server 2008 R2 Editions Comparison by Technical Specifications |archivedate=22 December 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222174550/http://www.microsoft.com/windowsserver2008/en/us/r2-compare-specs.aspx}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" width=30% | Features\n! scope=\"col\" width=10% | Foundation\n! scope=\"col\" width=10% | Standard\n! scope=\"col\" width=10% | Web\n! scope=\"col\" width=10% | [[High-performance computing|HPC]]\n! scope=\"col\" width=10% | Enterprise\n! scope=\"col\" width=10% | Datacenter\n! scope=\"col\" width=10% | Itanium\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | Maximum [[Random-access memory|RAM]] on [[x86-64]]\n| 8 GB || 32 GB || 32 GB || 256 GB || 2 TB || 2 TB || 2 TB\n|-\n! scope=\"row